<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South Carolina Track Star Turns Pro  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLUMBIA, S.C. (AP) -- Track star Terrance Trammell is turning
pro, giving up his final year of eligibility at South Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   Trammell, who will compete in the 110-meter hurdles at the
Olympics in Sydney in September, signed with agent Charley Wells of
Dallas. He is also considering endorsement deals with Nike and
adidas.
</P>
<P>
   ''I felt like I was ready to go to the next level,'' Trammell
said Monday. ''It was time to step up now with it being an Olympic
year. This was the best opportunity for me. It was one of those
things you don't pass up. I am excited about all the
opportunities.''
</P>
<P>
   Trammell was a two-time NCAA track athlete of the year and won
five NCAA titles and eight Southeastern Conference championships in
his three-year career at South Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   Trammell said he will return to school after the Olympics and
pursue his business degree while training under Gamecocks track
coach Curtis Frye.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
