<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-08 00:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Comets 71, Mercury 54  </HEADLINE>
By MEL REISNER
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX (AP) -- Tina Thompson, back at the scene of her MVP
performance in the WNBA All-Star Game, had 26 points and 10
rebounds as the Houston Comets beat the Phoenix Mercury 71-54
Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   Both teams earned playoff berths earlier, but the loss consigned
the Mercury (19-12) to fourth place in the Western Conference.
</P>
<P>
   Game 1 of the Mercury's first-round series with Los Angeles
begins Friday in Phoenix, and the Comets (26-5) begin the first
round at Sacramento on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Sheryl Swoopes had 19 points and eight rebounds for the Comets.
Brandy Reed scored 21 points and Jennifer Gillom 11 for Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   Three-time scoring champion Cynthia Cooper was held to just six
points -- only the second time in her career she didn't score in
double figures. Cooper also had six points in an 80-62 loss to
Phoenix on June 3.
</P>
<P>
   The Comets won their fourth straight road game to finish 13-3
away from the Compaq Center this season and took the series against
Phoenix, 2-1.
</P>
<P>
   Reed had a career-high 32 points in that game, but in the next
one last month Swoopes held her to six on 2-for-11 shooting.
</P>
<P>
   Swoopes had seven points during a 17-0 run by Houston midway
through the second half.
</P>
<P>
   The Mercury, who never led, tied it at 41 on a free throw by
Dena Head 7:39 into the second half. But Thompson gave the Comets
the lead with a three-point play 17 seconds later, and in the next
seven minutes Swoopes made three jumpers and a field goal, Thompson
made her fifth 3-pointer in five tries and Cooper made a basket.
</P>
<P>
   The Comets moved to a 58-41 lead with 5:06 to play.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson, who had an All-Star double-double in the America West
Arena three weeks ago, had seven points as the Comets took a 10-4
lead.
</P>
<P>
   But in the next 2:12, Gillom had a three-point play and made a
layup that tied it at 10. No more than five points separated the
teams until Swoopes threw a floor-length pass to Cooper for a layup
and a 39-33 Houston lead 3:54 into the second half.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-08-00 0003 </TRAILER>
