<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-08 00:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indians 2, Rangers 0  </HEADLINE>
By TOM WITHERS
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND (AP) -- Jim Thome, one of Cleveland's slowest runners,
scored on Travis Fryman's sacrifice fly in the seventh inning, and
Steve Woodard and four relievers combined on a five-hitter as the
Indians extended their winning streak to six with a 2-0 victory
over the Texas Rangers on Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   Thome reached around catcher Bill Haselman's tag to touch the
plate in the seventh and drove in Cleveland's other run with a
single in the eighth as the Indians matched their longest winning
streak this season.
</P>
<P>
   Cleveland, which hadn't won six in a row since April 7-12, got
its first shutout since May 11 and moved within 2&AMP;frac12; games of
Oakland, which leads the AL wild-card race.
</P>
<P>
   Gabe Kapler extended his hitting streak to 21 games for the
Rangers, who left the bases loaded in the fifth and sixth innings
and wasted a strong performance from starter Rick Helling (13-8).
</P>
<P>
   Helling allowed four hits in seven innings.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Reed (2-0) picked up the win after Woodard, pitching on
two days' rest, worked 5 2-3 scoreless innings for the Indians, who
are 7-3 since making a flurry of trading deadline moves.
</P>
<P>
   Reed and three other relievers then combined for 3 1-3 hitless
innings, with Bob Wickman pitching the ninth for his third save.
</P>
<P>
   Helling retired 12 straight before his first and only walk -- to
Thome -- opened the seventh. One out later, a perfectly executed
hit-and-run single by Wil Cordero sent Thome to third.
</P>
<P>
   Fryman then hit a fly ball to medium right where outfielder Chad
Curtis was in perfect position to make a strong throw home. He
fired to the plate on the fly, but it was a little high, giving
Thome the chance to slap the plate as he slid by.
</P>
<P>
   TV replays appeared to show that Haselman actually tagged Thome
on the left shoulder, but plate umpire Brian Runge ruled Thome
safe.
</P>
<P>
   In the eighth, Thome slapped an opposite-field RBI single to
left, scoring Omar Vizquel from second.
</P>
<P>
   Woodard was moved up in the rotation when scheduled starter Dave
Burba had to be pushed back until Wednesday because of a blister on
his right index finger.
</P>
<P>
   Woodard, acquired July 28 in a six-player deal with Milwaukee,
was sharp in his first outing for the Indians but lasted just three
innings his last start. Indians manager Charlie Manuel said before
the game that he didn't know what to expect.
</P>
<P>
   What Manuel and the Indians got was Woodard's best outing this
season.
</P>
<P>
   In the fourth, he snared a line drive by Rusty Greer to start an
inning-ending double play. Then in the fifth, after the Rangers put
two on with none out, left fielder Cordero made a leaping catch at
the wall to rob Ricky Ledee of extra bases.
</P>
<P>
   Woodard then struck out Haselman and walked Michael Lamb before
fanning Royce Clayton on a 3-2 pitch.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers again loaded the bases in the sixth off Woodard. But
Tom Martin came in and got pinch-hitter Curtis to ground out to
keep the game scoreless.
</P>
<P>
Notes: Texas and Cleveland met for the first time since swapping
Ledee and David Segui on July 28. Ledee went 0-for-2 before being
lifted for a pinch-hitter in sixth. Segui went 0-for-4. ... Greer's
double in the sixth was his 1,000th career hit. He is the sixth
player in Texas history to reach the plateau. ... Ledee, now with
his third team -- Yankees, Indians and Rangers -- this season, is
also wearing his fourth number. He wore No. 17 in New York, Nos. 22
and 23 with Cleveland and has No. 12 with Texas. ... Helling has
thrown an AL-high 2,800 pitches this season, an average of 112 per
start.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
