<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Erickson To Receive Elbow Surgery  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT (AP) -- Baltimore pitcher Scott Erickson will have a
ligament replaced in his right elbow, likely to sideline him for at
least a year.
</P>
<P>
   Erickson will be operated on Tuesday, with a tendon take from
his left wrist used to replace his ulnar collateral ligament,
Orioles trainer Richie Bancells said Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   ''Scotty has a long road ahead of him,'' Baltimore manager Mike
Hargrove said after the Orioles beat Detroit 4-3. ''I think we all
had a sneaking suspicion the outcome would be like this.''
</P>
<P>
   Erickson, 32, was 5-8 with a 7.87 ERA in his 11th major league
season. His last start was July 24.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Hargrove nor Bancells would speculate on how long it
will take Erickson to recover.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think next year's in doubt. It's safe to say the start of
the season's in doubt,'' Hargrove said.
</P>
<P>
   Bancells said 8-to-12 months is the usual recovery period.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's a chance he could (come back) at the end of next
season,'' Bancells said. ''It has a high rate of success.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-08-00 0016 </TRAILER>
