<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-08 00:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Orioles Renew Red Wings Agreement  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROCHESTER, N.Y. (AP) -- The Baltimore Orioles and Rochester Red
Wings on Monday signed a two-year renewal of the longest working
agreement in Triple-A baseball.
</P>
<P>
   Orioles owner Peter Angelos made his first trip to Rochester to
sign the agreement with Red Wings chief operating officer Naomi
Silver and president Gary Larder.
</P>
<P>
   Angelos has been the target of media and fan criticism in the
Flower City, where the Red Wings have not had a winning season
since winning the International League Governors' Cup playoffs in
1997.
</P>
<P>
   Rochester was 53-62 entering last night's game against Norfolk.
</P>
<P>
   ''I had never realized the importance of a managing general
partner going to the affiliates to meet everyone,'' Angelos said.
''I was concerned about keeping Rochester as part of the Oriole
family, but I never made an overt effort.''
</P>
<P>
   He bought the Orioles in 1993, and said at that time, ''Our farm
system had been pretty much neglected for a period of about 10
years. For the last six years we have been trying to build it up,
by signing players and spending tremendous sums of money.''
</P>
<P>
   I don't believe you can build a winner just through free
agency,'' said the man who seemed to be trying to do just that
before the Orioles moved four starting players at the July 31
trading deadline. ''You need a farm system too.''
</P>
<P>
   The Baltimore-Rochester agreement, which began in 1961, will
complete its 40th season in September. The only longer connections
in minor league baseball are between Baltimore and rookie-ball
Bluefield, W.Va., begun in 1958, and the Detroit Tigers and Class-A
Lakeland, Fla., since 1960.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
