<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-08 01:58 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Missile Defense Review Is Delayed  </HEADLINE>
By ROBERT BURNS
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Pentagon will take longer than expected to
prepare a recommendation to President Clinton on whether to move
forward with a national missile defense system, Defense Secretary
William Cohen said.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen issued a brief written statement Monday that said he would
need a few more weeks to consider the complex question, which
carries major implications for the defense budget and for U.S.
international relations.
</P>
<P>
   The secretary recently said he expected to make his
recommendation to Clinton by mid-August. Instead he is likely to
wait until early September, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   That still would give Clinton time to decide before leaving
office whether to authorize initial steps toward building a new
missile-tracking radar in Alaska -- a critical first step toward
eventual deployment of a national missile defense.
</P>
<P>
   ''A number of difficult issues remain to be resolved,'' Cohen
said.
</P>
<P>
   These issues, including whether the rocket booster to be used
for the anti-missile system can be ready for full-scale production
by 2003, must be settled before Cohen receives the Pentagon's
internal assessment, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Another unsettled question is whether the Pentagon should
proceed with the next flight test of the anti-missile system as
scheduled this fall. Officials are considering putting it off until
December or later. The failure of the two most recent flight tests,
including one in early July, raised questions about whether the
Pentagon was pushing too hard to meet a target date for deploying
the system by 2005.
</P>
<P>
   Pushing back the target date to 2006 or later probably would
increase the project's overall cost, another factor being weighed
by the Pentagon. Current cost estimates are about $60 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The internal review now under way is headed by Jacques Gansler,
the undersecretary of defense for acquisition and technology, and
officials of the Ballistic Missile Defense Organization, which runs
the project.
</P>
<P>
   ''I will make no recommendation about the future of the NMD
program until I have analyzed their findings,'' Cohen said. ''I
expect that to happen and to report to the president within the
next few weeks. Recent reports that I have made a decision on this
matter, preliminary or otherwise, are wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   ''There is no immediate or artificial deadline for a
recommendation to the president,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   ''My goal is to make the best possible recommendation, ... not
the earliest possible recommendation.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: Ballistic Missile Defense Organization:
http://www.acq.osd.mil/bmdo/bmdolink/html/nmd.html
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
