<DOCNO> APW20000808.0033 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-08 02:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lawyer jailed for violating probation  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   ROCHESTER, N.Y. (AP) - A judge in Monroe County ordered a
disbarred Rochester lawyer to prison after for failing to repay
money stolen from a client.
</P>
<P>
   William S. Wood was sentenced to serve one to three years behind
bars by Monroe County Court Judge Charles T. Maloy for violating
probation on his conviction for fourth-degree grand larceny.
</P>
<P>
   When Wood pleaded guilty two years ago, Maloy sentenced him to
five years' probation and ordered him to pay $46,000 in
restitution. But the judge found him in violation of his probation
last month because Wood repaid only $550 and didn't complete an
alcohol-rehabilitation program.
</P>
<P>
   Although Assistant District Attorney Jennifer Whitman asked that
Wood be sent to prison, Wood asked for another chance to fulfill
his obligations.
</P>
<P>
   But Maloy said Wood deserved prison time for shirking his
responsibilities and discrediting the legal profession.
</P>
<P>
   Wood, 44, stole the money from clients who were attempting to
foreclose on a property on which they held the mortgage.
</P>
<P>
   He collected the money from the property owner and deposited it
in his trust account but didn't turn over the money to his clients.
</P>
<P>
   The Appellate Division of state Supreme Court disbarred Wood in
November 1998, two months after he pleaded guilty and surrendered
his license to practice law.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
