<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-08 02:41 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lynne Cheney Talks To the AP  </HEADLINE>
By KAREN GULLO
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO (AP) -- Lynne Cheney knew her family life would not be
the same when a truck toting a satellite dish and a camera
suspended from a pole parked in front of her home in a Dallas
suburb soon before George W. Bush chose her husband as his running
mate.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney called it ''one of my endearing memories'' in an
Associated Press interview as she sat on a vintage train rumbling
through the countryside. With her on the train were more than 100
journalists, a slew of Secret Service agents, dozens of
20-something campaign workers and a mobile satellite dish for film
crews.
</P>
<P>
   It's only the beginning for Cheney, a writer, former talk show
pundit and well-known conservative crusader against ''political
correctness'' and nontraditional education. She plans to campaign
full-time with her husband Dick when he separates from Bush on the
campaign trail starting Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   She's considering doing fund-raisers; party operatives are eager
to get her on the circuit to capitalize on her popularity among the
party's right wing while Bush courts independents with John McCain
at his side.
</P>
<P>
   Her outspokenness, reputation for independence and passionate
political views have brought comparisons with Hillary Rodham
Clinton, which Cheney says is ''silly and irrelevant'' and took her
by surprise.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney said Democratic attacks on her husband's voting record --
he voted against a resolution calling, among other things, for
freeing Nelson Mandela from jail and against funding for Head Start
-- were ''a little dismaying and unpleasant,'' and amounted to
''people distorting the facts to gain political points.''
</P>
<P>
   She said her husband's votes had to be viewed in context. ''If
you look at the votes, many of them were about procedural issues''
brought up in a Democratically controlled House.
</P>
<P>
   The scrutiny that began when Bush picked her husband of 35 years
has only intensified. The attention is necessary, expected and
encouraged -- up to a point, said Cheney.
</P>
<P>
   Attracting the interest of swing voters who voted for President
Clinton 1992 and 1996 but might not want to vote Democratic this
year was the goal of a three-day, four-state train tour that ended
in Illinois Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's completely exhilarating,'' Cheney said near the end of
the tour after waving at confetti-strewn rallies and shaking hands
with supporters.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney said her role will be to travel with her husband and
speak out on education. A former head of the National Endowment for
the Humanities, Cheney has written extensively about her opposition
to nontraditional teaching methods that push aside drills,
memorization and testing in favor of less structured lesson plans.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney and other Republicans -- but also some Democrats -- favor a
return to traditional teaching methods.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney, a former policy adviser on education for Bush's campaign
and for the state of Texas, supports the governor's education
platform, which calls for testing kids to measure whether they are
meeting state-set standards of learning.
</P>
<P>
   Schools that don't measure up would lose federal funds and
parents would get federal money that they could use to send kids to
private schools.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents of standardized testing say it waters down lessons,
turns off students, hampers teachers creativity and is unfair to
some students.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney counters the formula has worked in Texas, where kids'
test scores are up. ''There's none of this silliness that kids have
the ability to learn things themselves,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The spotlight of the campaign has drawn attention to the Cheney
family, especially daughter Mary, a 31-year-old from Denver who is
gay. Numerous reports in the media have described her work for
Coors Brewery in Colorado, building good will for the company
within minority groups, including gays and lesbians.
</P>
<P>
   Lynne Cheney says she won't discuss the private lives of either
of her daughters -- she has another daughter Elizabeth, a lawyer and
mother of two.
</P>
<P>
   ''But every chance I get I'll also say that they are the most
terrific young women I've ever met and I hope everyone else
realizes ... what good and decent kids they are,'' Cheney said.
</P>
<P>
   Now an unpaid special assistant to her father, Mary Cheney is a
constant presence in her father's sphere of advisers and
strategists.
</P>
<P>
   The two share a passion for fly fishing, a sport that father
introduced his daughter to, said Lynne Cheney, who also tried fly
fishing. But instead of taking to the sport like Mary, she sent a
hook through her husband's earlobe.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-08-00 0241 </TRAILER>
