<DOCNO> APW20000808.0041 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-08 05:37 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Activist To Get Medal of Freedom  </HEADLINE>
By ANDREA CECIL
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT (AP) -- Growing up in the 1920s in Iowa, one group of
locals struck a chord so deep within Mildred ''Millie'' Jeffrey
that she never forgot how she felt.
</P>
<P>
   The Ku Klux Klan had a strong following in the Midwest in those
days.
</P>
<P>
   ''I remember the parades,'' Jeffrey said Monday. ''They had a
burning cross, and the men had the hoods over their heads and their
gowns.''
</P>
<P>
   Since there weren't many black in Cherokee, Iowa, for the KKK to
target, they concentrated on Jews and Catholics. Jeffrey said
children threw stones at her because she was the latter.
</P>
<P>
   ''No Catholic could get elected to public office, and I thought
it was very wrong and that's when I became interested in justice
and politics,'' she said. ''And that never left me.''
</P>
<P>
   For her lifetime achievement in such areas, President Clinton
was scheduled to award Jeffrey the Presidential Medal of Freedom on
Wednesday in Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   Jeffrey, 88, will be honored along with 14 others, including
former presidential candidate George McGovern, Sen. Daniel Patrick
Moynihan, Simon Wiesenthal and the Rev. Jesse Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   The medal is the highest civilian award, ranking second only to
the Congressional Medal of Honor, the nation's highest military
award.
</P>
<P>
   It is given to those individuals who have made special
contributions to the security or national interests of the country,
world peace, culture or any other significant arena.
</P>
<P>
   During the 1963 civil rights march that passed through
Montgomery, Ala., Jeffrey walked alongside the Rev. Martin Luther
King Jr. The same year, she marched to Jackson, Miss., with James
Meredith, the first black student admitted into the University of
Mississippi.
</P>
<P>
   ''White people were shouting epithets. It was very scary,''
Jeffrey said.
</P>
<P>
   Jeffrey was the director of the first woman's United Auto
Workers department. She was the president of the Michigan Women's
Foundation and was on the Wayne State University board of
governors.
</P>
<P>
   ''She's become such an icon for all of us because she never
slows down,'' said longtime friend Esther Shapiro. ''The only thing
is that she wears lower heels now.''
</P>
<P>
   Former UAW President Doug Fraser, who met Jeffrey in the 1950s,
said the freedom honor fits a woman who blazed a path.
</P>
<P>
   ''Millie was a pioneer. She's a woman of considerable ability.
She's always been in the fight for equality and social justice,''
Fraser said.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: http://www.whitehouse.gov
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-08-00 0537 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000808.0042 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-08 06:48 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton To Inspect Wildfire Damage  </HEADLINE>
By DEB RIECHMANN
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton is inspecting the smoky
wildfires in the West on Tuesday and talking with weary
firefighters who have blistered feet and bloodshot eyes from
battling blazes that have ravaged an area larger than the state of
Rhode Island.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's visit to the Payette National Forest in west-central
Idaho comes 26 days after a fire broke out there, scorching 23,000
acres -- so far -- of rugged, steep forestland. It is one of 65 fires
burning more than 826,800 acres in 10 states, according to the
National Interagency Fire Center in Idaho.
</P>
<P>
   ''They're the worst wildfires in 50 years and the president very
much wanted to go out there and see the people working on them,''
said White House spokesman Jake Siewert.
</P>
<P>
   The president will direct the secretaries of the Interior and
Agriculture departments to make recommendations on ways to
rehabilitate burned land and reduce fire risk to rural communities,
the White House said. He also will release $150 million in
emergency funds to the Agriculture Department for firefighting
efforts, according to a White House statement.
</P>
<P>
   An estimated 20,000 military and civilian firefighters are
working to contain blazes in Idaho, Nevada, New Mexico, Oregon,
Utah, Washington, Arizona, California, Colorado and Montana -- the
hardest hit by wildfires in the West.
</P>
<P>
   After taking a helicopter ride to view the damage, Clinton was
to have lunch and make remarks to some of the 1,276 people working
to contain the fire here near McCall, Idaho. The federal
firefighters work for the Forest Service, Bureau of Land
Management, National Park Service, Bureau of Indian Affairs and
Fish and Wildlife Service. There also are federal contract workers
and about 600 soldiers from Fort Hood, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Working 12-hour shifts, they mostly are digging up ground to
create fire lines.
</P>
<P>
   ''You use tools to scrape away anything that might burn so that
what you have left on your trail -- about 3 feet wide -- is bare
soil, which shouldn't burn,'' said Alexis Collins, a spokeswoman
for the Forest Service. ''It creates a fire break.''
</P>
<P>
   Digging fire lines is dirty work, she said, but not as dirty as
the job known as ''mopping up.''
</P>
<P>
   ''These people are digging in the ash, trying to disperse any
coals that are there,'' she said. ''That's real dirty work because
you're right in the ash. You come back black.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   National Interagency Fire Center: http://www.nifc.gov
</P>
<P>
   Forest Service links: http://www.fs.fed.us/fire/links2.shtml
</P>
</TEXT>
