<HEADLINE> Gilligan's Island Case Goes to Trial  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- After more than 30 years, two creators of
''Gilligan's Island'' are confident of finally being rescued in
their long battle over royalties from the 1960s television show.
</P>
<P>
   Elroy Schwartz, 77, and his writing partner Austin Kalish won a
judge's ruling Monday allowing their case to go to trial. They
claim that Schwartz's older brother, Sherwood Schwartz, cheated
them out of their share of millions of dollars.
</P>
<P>
   Attorneys for Sherwood Schwartz claimed the case was litigated
in the 1970s and there was no basis for it being considered again.
But Superior Court Judge David L. Minning rejected the argument
that the statute of limitations had expired.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit alleges fraud and breach of contract and seeks an
accounting of proceeds of the show since the early '70s. Sherwood
Schwartz was the show's producer. Elroy Schwartz and Kalish claim
they wrote most of the pilot script for the series.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're looking forward to righting a wrong,'' said the
Schwartz-Kalish team's attorney, Marc Toberoff.
</P>
<P>
   ''Gilligan's Island,'' which premiered in 1964, was canceled by
CBS in 1967 but has lived on in reruns since then.
</P>
</TEXT>
