<HEADLINE> Dow Gains 34; Nasdaq Adds 12  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks continued their advance in early trading
Tuesday after a report showing rising worker productivity added to
the growing belief that interest rates will remain steady.
</P>
<P>
   In the first hour of trading on Wall Street, the Dow Jones
industrial average was up 33.70 at 10,900.01, adding to Monday's
99-point gain.
</P>
<P>
   Broader stock indicators also rose. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500
index was up 0.50 at 1,479.82 , and the Nasdaq composite index was
up 11.50 at 3,872.44 after rising 75 points Monday.
</P>
<P>
   A report from the Labor Department Tuesday further eased
investors worries over interest rates. Americans' productivity, a
key measure of rising living standards, surged 5.3 percent in the
second quarter, putting productivity gains during the past year at
the fastest pace in 17 years.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Reserve has counted on gains in worker productivity
to offset labor shortages that have boosted wages -- a possible
inflationary signal.
</P>
<P>
   The productivity report is one of several recent economic
indicators that show inflation remaining in check.
</P>
<P>
   Technology stocks were mixed in the early going Tuesday as
investors waited for Cisco Systems' second quarter earnings report
to be issued after the market closed.
</P>
<P>
   Verizon Communications, the offspring of the Bell Atlantic-GTE
merger that has been struck by communications workers, released
second-quarter earnings that fell short of forecasts. Shares of
Verizon fell $3.75 to $44.
</P>
<P>
   But wireless giant Nokia added $1 to $39.50 and Clear Channel
Communications gained $2.75 to $80.50.
</P>
<P>
   Leading the Dow higher again was Eastman Kodak, up $2 to $60.25.
</P>
<P>
   Declining issues outnumbered advancers by a narrow margin on the
New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 134.18 million
shares, up from Monday's pace.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index was down 0.30 at 509.57.
</P>
<P>
   Overseas, Japan's Nikkei stock average fell 1.14 percent. In
afternoon trading, Germany's DAX index was up 1.02 percent,
Britain's FT-SE 100 was up 0.34 percent, and France's CAC-40 was up
0.69 percent.
</P>
<P>
