<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Venezuela Leader To Walk Into Iraq  </HEADLINE>
By DIANA ELIAS
<TEXT>
<P>
   KUWAIT (AP) -- When Venezuelan President Hugo Chavez becomes the
first foreign leader to visit Iraq since the Gulf War, it will be
on foot, ducking a U.N. ban on flying to the isolated country.
</P>
<P>
   The Venezuelan Foreign Ministry confirmed Tuesday that Chavez
would walk across the border from Iran to Iraq as part of his
whirlwind tour of fellow members of the Organization of Petroleum
Exporting Countries, or OPEC.
</P>
<P>
   The Foreign Ministry provided no other details. Until now,
Venezuelan authorities had been closemouthed about the logistics of
a trip that has angered the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking from Baghdad, Jose A. Rodrigues de la Sierra, first
secretary of the Venezuelan Embassy, said Chavez will fly to the
Iran-Iraq border Thursday afternoon after meetings with Iranian
leaders, then walk across the frontier near the Iranian border town
of Kermanshah, some 300 miles west of Tehran. It was not clear
whether Chavez would then helicopter or drive to Baghdad, about 200
miles further west.
</P>
<P>
   Without U.N. permission, international flights to and from Iraq
are barred under sanctions imposed to punish it for its 1990
invasion of Kuwait. The invasion was reversed by the U.S.-led Gulf
War in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. State Department said Monday it was ''particularly
galling'' that the first such visit is being made by a leader who
was democratically elected.
</P>
<P>
   But Kuwaiti economist Jassem al-Saadoun said Tuesday Chavez's
visit to Iraq should not be blown out of proportion.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a protocol visit,'' al-Saadoun said Tuesday. ''Kuwait has
no objection to anyone visiting Iraq. I believe Kuwait
understands.''
</P>
<P>
   Kuwait's official silence appeared to confirm al-Saadoun's
assessment. Chavez arrived in Kuwait Tuesday for meetings with the
Gulf state's leaders as part of his OPEC tour.
</P>
<P>
   Al-Saadoun said Chavez's trip could have economic benefits if he
is able to persuade OPEC members to stick to a pricing strategy
designed to prevent oil prices from going too low or too high. The
tour is aimed at forging unity among OPEC's fractious members.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-08-00 1146 </TRAILER>
