<DOCNO> APW20000808.0057 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-08 12:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Koreans Chosen for Family Reunions  </HEADLINE>
By KYONG-HWA SEOK
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEOUL, South Korea (AP) -- Last month, Shin Myong-ja learned her
daughter did not die during the Korean War as she thought, but was
living in North Korea. On Tuesday, another dream came true: Shin,
93, was told her daughter will visit her.
</P>
<P>
   ''I can't even remember her face,'' an elated Shin said. Her
daughter, 68-year-old Park Ryang Sun, disappeared during the chaos
of the 1950-53 war.
</P>
<P>
   Shin was told by Red Cross officials that she was among South
Koreans who will meet family members from communist North Korea for
the first time since they were separated a half-century ago.
</P>
<P>
   Building on a mood of reconciliation after an unprecedented
summit of their leaders in June, North and South Korea on Tuesday
exchanged the names of 100 people each who will cross their heavily
armed border next week for temporary family reunions in Seoul and
Pyongyang.
</P>
<P>
   The four-day reunions beginning Aug. 15 are the first since 50
people from each side crossed the border in 1985.
</P>
<P>
   Chang Yi-yoon, now 72, was separated from his family 50 years
ago when Korea divided into two nations. The South Korean laborer
learned the amazing news last month that his 109-year-old mother is
alive.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's unbelievable that at that age, my mother is alive. It's
like a dream,'' Chang was quoted as saying by the state Yonhap news
agency.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, he learned he will be allowed to go north to see
her.
</P>
<P>
   ''I will make a deep bow and hold her in a long, warm embrace,''
he has said.
</P>
<P>
   Park Jae-yoon, a 53-year-old South Korean, and two siblings
sobbed when they heard that they their 71-year-old brother, Park
Jae Young, will visit them.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't know what he did for a living. I don't know if he has
a family. And I can't remember what he was like,'' Park Jae-yoon
said.
</P>
<P>
   The oldest Park disappeared during the war. His family in South
Korea learned he was in North Korea in the 1980s through defectors
and other channels, but could not contact him.
</P>
<P>
   Kim Joon-sup, a 66-year-old Seoul resident, bought gifts,
including six watches, two cameras and two calculators, when he
heard he will travel to North Korea to meet a brother and a sister.
</P>
<P>
   ''I can't sleep at night. I'm curious and worried whether he'll
recognize me,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Kim, originally from Pyongyang, was captured by the South Korean
military while fighting for North Korea during the war. Later he
served in the South Korean military.
</P>
<P>
   To increase the chances of reunions, the Koreas had exchanged
the lists of 200 candidates each to check whether long-lost
relatives could be found.
</P>
<P>
   More than 70,000 people in South Korea applied to be reunited
with relatives in the North. Authorities used a computer lottery to
choose 100 finalists.
</P>
<P>
   North Korea's list includes a renowned painter, poet, actor,
professor and other well-known people. It is not known how they
were selected, but observers in South Korea have speculated they
were chosen partly for their loyalty to the totalitarian state.
</P>
<P>
   South Koreans who made the cut of 200 candidates but were not
finalists, were deeply disappointed.
</P>
<P>
   ''I am old. And I really want to see my daughter. But they say I
can't go,'' said 91-year-old Bang Jin-kwan. His daughter was 5 when
he left her at his brother's home in the North and made the arduous
journey south as a refugee.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-08-00 1208 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000808.0058 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-08 12:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Group Urges Ban on Cluster Bombs  </HEADLINE>
By SUE LEEMAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON (AP) -- In Kosovo alone, cluster bombs have been blamed
for killing and maiming more than 200 civilians.
</P>
<P>
   Calling for a global moratorium on cluster bombs, an anti-land
mine group said Tuesday nearly a third of the devices fail to
explode on impact -- remaining potentially lethal to unwary
passers-by.
</P>
<P>
   ''The continued use of cluster bombs has cost thousands of
civilian lives, denied land to the poor ... and is now costing the
international community millions to eradicate'' unexploded devices,
the U.K. Working Group on Land Mines said in a report.
</P>
<P>
   Cluster bombs, composed of scores of small bombs that scatter to
create a wider area of explosion, were used against troops, weapons
and armored vehicles during conflicts in Vietnam, the Persian Gulf
and in NATO's 1999 bombing campaign against Yugoslavia aimed at
ending repression of ethnic Albanians in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   In June, U.N. officials trying to clear Kosovo of unexploded
ordnance criticized NATO for failing to provide information about
the location of the devices.
</P>
<P>
   The same month, the Yugoslav war crimes tribunal said it would
not investigate NATO for criminal activity during the Kosovo
campaign. Cluster bombs and weapons using depleted uranium, which
were both denounced by human rights groups, were not banned by
international law, the tribunal said.
</P>
<P>
   Although the bombs are designed to detonate on impact, the U.K.
Working Group on Land Mines said research showed between 9 percent
and 30 percent of the devices failed to do so because of
manufacturing defects and problems with soft landings.
</P>
<P>
   The U.K. Working Group said studies showed up to 12 percent of
British cluster bombs used in Kosovo failed to explode on impact.
The Ministry of Defense said the manufacturer reported that the
failure rate of the British cluster bombs was about 5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ''The unexploded bomblets effectively turn into land mines,
ready to detonate on contact, causing death and injury to civilians
even many years after the war has ended,'' said Richard Lloyd,
director of the group, which is the British arm of the
International Campaign to Ban Land Mines.
</P>
<P>
   ''As many are brightly colored and the size of a drinks can,
they are particularly attractive to children,'' Lloyd added.
</P>
<P>
   The report concluded that because the weapons failed to
distinguish between soldiers and civilians, their use was
indiscriminate and breached international law.
</P>
<P>
   The working group called for a global moratorium on the use,
manufacture and sale of cluster bombs pending an in-depth review of
their legality and impact.
</P>
<P>
   It said there should be international laws to require nations
using cluster bombs to clear them after a conflict, compensate
injured civilians and hand over full records of cluster bomb
deployment to the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
   In a report published in June, Britain's Ministry of Defense
said cluster bombs are ''an effective weapon against area targets
such as a group of soft-skinned military vehicles,'' but said it
was testing missiles as a way to target single vehicles more
effectively.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-08-00 1226 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000808.0059 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-08 12:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Meningitis Outbreaks in Russia  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW (AP) -- Nearly 350 children have contracted meningitis in
Russia's Far East, and scores have been hospitalized because of the
potentially fatal disease.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-three children were hospitalized Monday in the city of
Komsomolsk-on-Amur, about 3,900 miles east of Moscow, the Emergency
Situations Ministry said, according to the ITAR-Tass news agency.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, 127 children were hospitalized with the infection,
which strikes the linings of the brain and spinal cord. An
additional 198 children have been treated and released, ITAR-Tass
said.
</P>
<P>
   The last outbreak on such a scale in the region was in 1991,
when 487 people were afflicted, according to local epidemiologists.
</P>
<P>
   A separate menigitis outbreak was reported in the southern
Russian region of Stavropol, where 32 elementary children have been
hospitalized since July, ITAR-Tass reported.
</P>
<P>
   Outbreaks of contagious diseases have become increasingly common
in Russia because of a lack of funding for medical services.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
