<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Closes Polluting Company  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING (AP) -- China said Tuesday it shut down a state-run metal
company that for years spewed enormous amounts of sulfur dioxide
and other pollutants into the air.
</P>
<P>
   The Shenyang Smeltery is China's first large government
enterprise to be closed because of pollution, the state-run Xinhua
News Agency said. It was closed in June.
</P>
<P>
   The factory, in an industrialized part of northeast China,
discharged 74,000 tons of sulfur dioxide and 67 tons of heavy
metals annually, Xinhua said.
</P>
<P>
   The factory polluted about 20 square miles of Shenyang and
produced 42 percent of the sulfur dioxide found in the city, once
among the 10 most polluted in the world, Xinhua said.
</P>
<P>
   Residents suffered health problems, and area officials appealed
repeated to the central government for help, the report said.
</P>
<P>
   ''We can breathe some fresh air from now on,'' Xinhua quoted
resident Liu Shuying as saying.
</P>
<P>
   Founded in 1936, the Shenyang Smeltery was among China's top 500
state-owned enterprises in the 1980s, refining gold, silver,
copper, lead and zinc.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
