<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Venezuela Leader To Go to Iraq  </HEADLINE>
By DIANA ELIAS
<TEXT>
<P>
   KUWAIT (AP) -- When Venezuelan President Hugo Chavez becomes the
first foreign leader to visit Iraq since the Gulf War, it will be
by car, ducking a U.N. ban on flying to the isolated country.
</P>
<P>
   Venezuela's foreign minister, Jose Vicente Rangel, said Tuesday
in Caracas that Chavez will cross the border from Iran by car, not
by foot as Foreign Ministry officials had said earlier in the day.
</P>
<P>
   Chavez is on a whirlwind tour of fellow members of the
Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking from Baghdad, Jose A. Rodrigues de la Sierra, first
secretary of the Venezuelan Embassy, said Chavez will fly to the
Iran-Iraq border Thursday afternoon after meetings with Iranian
leaders, then cross the frontier near the Iranian border town of
Kermanshah, 300 miles west of Tehran. It was not clear whether
Chavez would then helicopter or drive to Baghdad, about 200 miles
further west.
</P>
<P>
   Without U.N. permission, international flights to and from Iraq
are barred under sanctions imposed to punish it for its 1990
invasion of Kuwait. The invasion was reversed by the U.S.-led Gulf
War in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. State Department said Monday it was ''particularly
galling'' that the first such visit is being made by a leader who
was democratically elected.
</P>
<P>
   But Kuwaiti economist Jassem al-Saadoun said Chavez's visit to
Iraq should not be blown out of proportion.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a protocol visit,'' al-Saadoun said. ''Kuwait has no
objection to anyone visiting Iraq. I believe Kuwait understands.''
</P>
<P>
   Kuwait's official silence appeared to confirm al-Saadoun's
assessment. Chavez arrived in Kuwait on Tuesday for meetings with
the Gulf state's leaders as part of his OPEC tour.
</P>
<P>
   Al-Saadoun said Chavez's trip could have economic benefits if he
is able to persuade OPEC members to stick to a pricing strategy
designed to prevent oil prices from going too low or too high. The
tour is aimed at forging unity among OPEC's fractious members.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-08-00 1441 </TRAILER>
