<DOCNO> APW20000808.0075 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-08 14:44 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tension High on West Bank  </HEADLINE>
By DINA KRAFT
<TEXT>
<P>
   ELON MOREH, West Bank (AP) -- In this Jewish settlement,
residents run home guard drills, fearful they may one day be
overrun by Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   In the neighboring Palestinian village of Salim, Palestinians
keep their herds locked up so they don't have to venture to
outlying pastures, site of recent clashes with armed settlers from
Elon Moreh in a land dispute.
</P>
<P>
   Fear and friction, always part of life in the contested West
Bank, are intensifying as Israel and the Palestinians try to
conclude a land-for-peace deal.
</P>
<P>
   Many settlers feel besieged. ''People are talking about war,''
said Mikki Miller-Mendelson, a mother of eight, of concerns the
settlements could one day be attacked by large numbers of
Palestinians. Miller-Mendelson's husband was killed by Palestinian
militants in a 1991 shooting near the settlement of Dolev.
</P>
<P>
   At Elon Moreh -- located near Nablus, a Palestinian city with a
population more than 100 times the settlement of 1,200 -- defiance
was the message. ''We will never leave,'' proclaimed a larger
banner fluttering above rows of red-roofed homes.
</P>
<P>
   In Salim, in the valley below, Khaled Ishtaya, the mukhtar, or
village elder, nervously fingered brown worry beads as he recited a
litany of complaints against Elon Moreh. Settlers have stolen
sheep, uprooted olive trees, threatened Salim residents at
gunpoint, Ishtaya said.
</P>
<P>
   ''There must be peace but with these people we can know no
peace. They are thieves -- land thieves,'' said Ishtaya, 52.
</P>
<P>
   Villagers said that over the weekend, settlers carrying sticks
and pistols attacked three Salim shepherds grazing their flock on a
disputed hillside. The shepherds fled, leaving some 400 sheep
behind.
</P>
<P>
   One of the shepherds who said he was beaten had stitches on his
nose and rolled up his sleeve to reveal a purple welt of bruises.
</P>
<P>
   Salim residents say the hill belongs to them, part of an expanse
of pastures they have used for generations. The settlers contend
the hilltop is within the settlement's municipal boundaries.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, there was a second clash between stone-throwing
villagers and gun-toting settlers. At one point, Lt. Col. Baruch
Yedid, the Israeli commander in charge of coordinating local
security activity with the Palestinian Authority, was wrestled to
the ground by two young settlers.
</P>
<P>
   Yedid said he was hit with a club on the neck, choked and kicked
in the back. Leaders of Elon Moreh blamed Yedid, saying the officer
has a history of siding with the Palestinians and provoked the
settlers.
</P>
<P>
   Amichai Remer, 30, who deals with security at Elon Moreh, also
dismissed the Palestinians' complaints. No trees have been
uprooted, no weapons waved, no sheep or donkeys stolen, Remer said.
</P>
<P>
   He said the Palestinians have become more brazen because of
progress toward a land-for-peace treaty at Camp David last month.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak has offered to hand over more
than 90 percent of the West Bank to the Palestinians, and has said
at least 20 percent of the 200,000 settlers will not come under
Israeli sovereignty, meaning they either have to leave their homes
or live under Palestinian rule.
</P>
<P>
   Fearing a final peace deal, settlers have re-established several
rogue outposts in recent weeks in an attempt to prevent the
territory from being handed over to the Palestinians. The Haaretz
daily said Tuesday that at nine sites, settlers have set up mobile
homes, paved roads and poured cement foundations.
</P>
<P>
   Settlers say a previous deal with Barak to refrain from
unauthorized construction is off because of the concessions he made
to the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is the prime minister who has broken the agreement in a
flagrant manner,'' said Bentzy Lieberman, a settler leader.
</P>
<P>
   Remer said the threat to settlements has grown since Camp David.
</P>
<P>
   Settlers are preparing for the possibility large numbers of
Palestinians might storm the Israeli enclaves, running self-defense
drills and stockpiling weapons in coordination with the Israeli
army. At Dolev, residents have been told to hoard supplies.
</P>
<P>
   ''Everyone has an assignment, everyone knows what to do. Some
will handle weaponry, others will direct the operation,'' Remer
said.
</P>
<P>
   In neighboring Salim, residents are trying to stay clear of the
settlers.
</P>
<P>
   Maruf Ishtaya, 60, is keeping his sheep at home so his son won't
become a target in the pastures. ''I'm scared for my son who was
attacked Saturday, afraid they (the settlers) will kill him.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
