<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kosovo Court Acquits Serb Family  </HEADLINE>
By ALISON MUTLER
<TEXT>
<P>
   GNJILANE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- In a case that was closely watched
as a test of the judicial system in Kosovo, a court on Tuesday
cleared a Serb father and his two sons of murdering an ethnic
Albanian.
</P>
<P>
   The man died in a July 1999 gun battle involving U.S. soldiers,
and an Army sergeant testified Monday that he shot at an ethnic
Albanian who was firing at U.S. troops that day. The five-member
panel of judges ruled there wasn't enough evidence to convict the
three men of killing Afrim Gagica.
</P>
<P>
   Mirolub Momcilovic, 60, dropped his head in relief when the
verdict was announced, and hugged his sons, Boban, 25, and
Jugoslav, 32. Boban burst into tears.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm happy to be free,'' he said. ''I didn't kill that guy.''
</P>
<P>
   However, because prosecutors have 15 days to appeal, the father
and sons were returned to the U.S. Army's detention facility at
Camp Bondsteel to await further court action. They have been
incarcerated since the July 10, 1999, shooting.
</P>
<P>
   The three Serbs were convicted of illegal firearms possession,
but were sentenced to time served.
</P>
<P>
   The case against the three Serbs had cast doubt on whether
minorities could get a fair trial in Kosovo's ethnically-charged
courts. It drew attention because the events leading up to Gagica's
slaying were captured on videotape surveillance cameras outside the
family's home.
</P>
<P>
   Though the tape did not show who shot Gagica, U.S. soldiers are
heard on the tape arriving at the scene. Defense attorneys argued
it was unclear who fired the fatal shot.
</P>
<P>
   The initial U.S. Army report of the incident found that Gagica
and others had come to the Momcilovic home ''with criminal
intent.'' Nevertheless, the father and sons were charged with
murder and the trial began in April.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't until a year after the trial began that it surfaced
that American soldiers had shot at a man in a shed where Gagica was
hunkered down.
</P>
<P>
   The United Nations quickly praised the acquittal. U.N.
spokeswoman Susan Manuel cited the presence of French judge Patrice
de Charette in the ruling by a panel with a majority of ethnic
Albanian judges.
</P>
<P>
   ''We do feel that the presence of the international judge helped
justice to be served,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Attacks on minorities in Kosovo have persisted despite the
presence of thousands of NATO-led peacekeepers who took over
control of the province after a 78-day air war against Yugoslavia
in 1999.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-08-00 1453 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
