<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-08 15:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lebanon To Deploy Forces in South  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) -- Lebanon announced Tuesday it will begin
deploying its security forces in southern Lebanon, an area
patrolled by Shiite Muslim guerrillas since Israel's withdrawal in
May.
</P>
<P>
   The force of 1,000 Lebanese soldiers and policemen will begin
fanning out in ''liberated areas'' at dawn Wednesday, Interior
Minister Michel Murr said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   U.N. peacekeepers moved into the zone Saturday -- a step Lebanon
had made a prerequisite for its own deployment -- but tension
continues to simmer and has drawn warnings from Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Four people were wounded in the zone Sunday and Monday when
Israeli soldiers fired at stone-throwers and youths preparing to
hurl a firebomb over the border fence.
</P>
<P>
   Israel's Deputy Defense Minister Ephraim Sneh said Tuesday he
doubted the Lebanese government really intended to take control
from the guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
   ''What has to worry us is whether it will be a genuine
deployment or a make-believe deployment, and at present the
impression is that it will be a make-believe deployment,'' Sneh
told reporters on a visit to the Israeli side of the border.
</P>
<P>
   Murr said Saturday there would be no armed guerrilla presence in
the area after the Lebanese forces were deployed.
</P>
<P>
   Witnesses said Tuesday that armed members of the most active
guerrilla group, the Iranian-backed Hezbollah, still manned some
positions in the zone. But guerrillas were seen removing banners
and signs from some positions Tuesday evening.
</P>
<P>
   The guerrillas have pledged to cooperate with the Lebanese
authorities after the Israeli withdrawal. Hezbollah's leader, Sheik
Hassan Nasrallah, has said his fighters would not serve as a
substitute for the government in maintaining law and order in the
zone.
</P>
<P>
   Murr has said the 500 soldiers and 500 policemen will be under
the Interior Ministry's command and their job will be to maintain
law and order in the zone. They will be joining a few hundred
policemen deployed shortly after Israel's May 24 withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
   He said Lebanese security forces will not deploy along the
border, saying that job is for the U.N. peacekeepers. Lebanon has
repeatedly refused to send troops from its 75,000-strong army to
its southern frontier, saying it does not want to serve as Israel's
border guard.
</P>
<P>
   The Lebanese deployment appears to be a token force for a region
that covers 10 percent of Lebanon and has seen bloody conflict for
nearly 30 years. It seems designed to meet U.N. and Western demands
that the government show a semblance of authority in southern
Lebanon and pave the way for foreign aid for the reconstruction of
the war-ravaged south.
</P>
<P>
   The decision to deploy was made Tuesday after a meeting of
senior Lebanese army officers and the U.N. peacekeeping force.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-08-00 1504 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
