<HEADLINE> 14 Killed in Clash in Angola  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   LUANDA, Angola (AP) -- A three-hour gunbattle between rebel
forces and government troops just east of the capital left 10
rebels and four civilians dead, the government said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the rebel group UNITA attacked at dawn Monday in the
town of Catete, 30 miles east of the Angolan capital, Luanda,
according to an armed forces statement. There was no information on
government casualties.
</P>
<P>
   Before fleeing, the rebels looted a World Food Program warehouse
and held 150 civilians hostage, a according to Radio Ecclesia. The
rebels also targeted military posts and local government buildings,
Ecclesia said, citing an army official.
</P>
<P>
   A power outage occurred in large areas of Luanda at about the
same time as the Catete attack and continued Tuesday afternoon.
Local power company spokesman Joao Simao said the army was using a
helicopter to look for evidence of sabotaged power lines.
</P>
<P>
   There was no comment from the rebel group UNITA, a
Portuguese-language acronym for the National Union for the Total
Independence of Angola.
</P>
<P>
   The government and UNITA have engaged in low-level fighting
since the army ousted the rebels from their central highland
strongholds after months of conventional warfare around major
provincial cities.
</P>
<P>
   Angola's civil war began after independence from Portugal in
1975. A 4-year-old peace pact unraveled and fighting restarted in
December 1998.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
