<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Concerned Over Kashmir Tensions  </HEADLINE>
By BARRY SCHWEID
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The United States is trying again to ease
tensions between India and Pakistan, two quarreling South Asia
neighbors who have fought three wars in the past 53 years and now
have nuclear weapons.
</P>
<P>
   Last spring, President Bill Clinton warned that South Asia was
the most perilous region in the world.
</P>
<P>
   Their dispute over the Himalayan territory of Kashmir, where a
secessionist uprising has raged for more than 11 years, grew more
ominous Tuesday when a Kashmiri militant group called off its
cease-fire with India.
</P>
<P>
   The State Department proposed ''direct discussion'' between
India and Pakistan, but left it to the two sides to figure out how
to get together.
</P>
<P>
   India has refused to negotiate with Pakistan over Kashmir. In
response, the militant Kashmiri group Hezb-ul Mujahedeen called off
its cease-fire, rekindling concerns in Washington over events in
the region.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have had, as you know, continuing concerns about tensions
between India and Pakistan, particularly over Kashmir,'' State
Department spokesman Richard Boucher said Tuesday. ''We've also
been concerned about the threat to regional stability in South Asia
that's posed by the introduction of nuclear weapons to the
region.''
</P>
<P>
   Kashmir is one of the most volatile regions in the world.
</P>
<P>
   ''We encourage and support whatever steps the two countries will
take to reduce violence and resolve the differences, including
dialogue between them,'' Boucher said.
</P>
<P>
   Divided between Pakistan and India after British rule of the
subcontinent ended in 1947, Kashmir has been the flashpoint for two
of the three wars between the uneasy neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   Both countries claim Kashmir in its entirety.
</P>
<P>
   Pakistan has been pressing for a vote by Kashmiris on both the
Indian and Pakistani sides of the territory to decide whether a
united Kashmir would join Islamic Pakistan or Hindu India.
</P>
<P>
   A 1948 United Nations resolution calls for the vote, which India
opposes.
</P>
<P>
   Boucher said the U.S. government regretted the decision by the
Hezb-ul Mujahedeen to call off its cease-fire with India, and said
''we would urge all sides to nurture and continue the process of
peace.''
</P>
<P>
   Addressing India and Pakistan, Boucher said ''it's reasonable
for the parties to sit down together to work on peace and to work
out the structure of the talks.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   Library of Congress profile of India:
http://lcweb2.loc.gov/frd/cs/intoc.html
</P>
<P>
   of Pakistan: http://lcweb2.loc.gov/frd/cs/pktoc.html
</P>
</TEXT>
