<DOCNO> APW20000808.0094 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-08 16:44 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bandits Rob Italian Freight Train  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROME (AP) -- Thieves used a homemade stop light Tuesday to rob an
Italian freight train loaded with cigarettes craved by black
marketeers.
</P>
<P>
   The holdup was the third robbery of a freight train carrying
cigarettes in southern Italy in less than four months, Italian news
reports said.
</P>
<P>
   Police said a band of about a dozen bandits planted a homemade
red light on the tracks in the countryside in the Puglia region in
southeastern Italy, making the Sicily-bound train to halt.
</P>
<P>
   The gang made off with about two tons of cigarettes legally
manufactured by Italy's state tobacco monopoly and loaded them onto
a truck. Police, alerted about the holdup, began searching for the
bandits and found the truck abandoned along with its cargo not far
away, authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   Many Italian smokers feed their nicotine habit with contraband
cigarettes bought on the street from black-market vendors, avoiding
steep taxes.
</P>
<P>
   But crackdowns on smugglers bringing in bootleg smokes in
speedboats across the Adriatic Sea from former Yugoslavia have left
the black marketeers short of merchandise, authorities say.
</P>
<P>
   The scope of contraband cigarette trafficking was underlined
last month when the head of a state criminal court in neighboring
Switzerland was arrested on corruption charges. Italian anti-Mafia
investigators had photographed the official with an alleged top
international cigarette smuggler.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-08-00 1644 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000808.0095 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-08 16:45 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> During private law career, Lieberman courted politics  </HEADLINE>
By ADAM GORLICK
<TEXT>
<P>
   As a civil lawyer in the 1970s and early 1980s, Connecticut Sen.
Joseph Lieberman spent more time courting his political interests
than developing legal ones. And that was fine with his colleagues,
who knew from the start that Lieberman's calling was public
service, not private practice.
</P>
<P>
   After graduating from Yale Law School in 1967, Lieberman joined
Wiggin &AMP; Dana, a New Haven law firm that assigned him mostly to
run-of-the-mill civil cases.
</P>
<P>
   ''There were two impressions everyone had of Joe,'' said Noel
Hanf, managing partner of Wiggin &AMP; Dana, who was hired at the firm
at about the time Lieberman left. ''One was that he was very bright
and focused. The other was that his horizons were always broader
than private practice.''
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman left Wiggin &AMP; Dana in 1969 to write ''The Power
Broker,'' a profile of Democratic National Chairman John M. Bailey.
A year later he won his first state Senate seat, and in 1972
started his own firm with Ted Baldwin - now New Haven's corporation
counsel.
</P>
<P>
   ''Joe was more of a counselor than a litigator,'' Baldwin said.
''He gave people advice, and that's what the clients appreciated
from him.''
</P>
<P>
   The cases that Lieberman took on were unremarkable - mostly real
estate closings and limited corporation work.
</P>
<P>
   ''He treated the Senate position as a full-time job,'' said Jim
Segaloff, who added his name to the Baldwin &AMP; Lieberman firm as a
full partner in 1973.
</P>
<P>
   ''I was interested in practicing law, and it was understood that
Joe would pursue his political thing,'' Segaloff said. ''That was
fine with everyone.''
</P>
<P>
   Baldwin left the firm by 1979, but Lieberman and Segaloff spent
the next 12 years as partners.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't think his focus at that time was on being an attorney
so much as being a state senator,'' said state Attorney General
Richard Blumenthal. ''He made a living as a lawyer, but he was
always looking beyond that.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1983, Lieberman began his six-year stint as Connecticut's
attorney general. Still a part-time job at the time, Lieberman kept
his stake in the New Haven law firm until 1985, when he turned his
full attention to politics.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't think that Joe would necessarily have made a better
politician than lawyer,'' Baldwin said. ''He had a calling to
public service, and he followed it. If his calling was to the law,
he would have been as successful in that field as he has been in
politics.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-08-08-00 1645 </TRAILER>
