<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-08 17:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Man killed by slow-moving freight train  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   PORT CRANE, N.Y. (AP) - A slow-moving freight train struck and
killed a man late Monday night, authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   The accident that killed 22-year-old David Mulcahy of Port Crane
occurred at around 11:40 p.m. on tracks just north of Binghamton,
according to Broome County Sheriff David Harder.
</P>
<P>
   Train operators told investigators the train was traveling at
around 34 miles per hour when they spotted Mulcahy on the tracks.
The operators were unable to stop the train in time to avoid
striking Mulcahy, whose legs were severed on impact, Harder said
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ''The engineer saw something and blew the horn,'' Harder said.
''The victim's legs were across the tracks. He raised his head up,
looked at him, and just laid there. You can't stop a train on a
dime. Eighteen cars went by before it came to a stop.''
</P>
<P>
   Harder said the accident was not yet classified as a suicide,
but he said that hasn't been ruled out.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-08-08-00 1701 </TRAILER>
