<DOCNO> APW20000808.0099 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-08 17:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chavez Asks Cabinet To Resign  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   CARACAS, Venezuela (AP) -- President Hugo Chavez has asked his
entire cabinet to resign as part of plan to reorganize the
government and revive the flagging economy following his landslide
re-election.
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Isaias Rodriguez announced the move Tuesday,
saying some cabinet ministers would be reinstated following the
resignations, and others would leave their posts for good.
</P>
<P>
   ''The idea is to keep functionaries who should be kept and
replace others in order to carry out the policy of rescuing the
country from the economic crisis,'' Rodriguez told reporters.
</P>
<P>
   Chavez won a new six-year term in general elections on July 30,
and though his popularity is strong it has been eroded by a
punishing recession that saw the economy shrink by seven percent
last year.
</P>
<P>
   Chavez, who is currently on a trip to the Middle East visiting
fellow members of the Organization of Petroleum Exporting
Countries, has vowed to make the economy his top priority going
into his new term.
</P>
<P>
   His economic team has often been accused of being incompetent,
but Chavez has repeatedly refused requests that they be sacked. It
wasn't immediately clear what the latest cabinet reshuffle would
mean for key economic posts.
</P>
<P>
   The economic woes came despite a boom in the price of petroleum,
Venezuela's main export. Oil prices have quadrupled since Chavez
took office in February 1999. Chavez's critics say his scathing
verbal attacks on business leaders have created a hostile climate
for investment.
</P>
<P>
   The economy is slowly recovering, however, with the government
reporting gross domestic product growing by 0.3 percent in the
year's first quarter and by about 2 percent in the second quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Chavez, a former paratrooper who staged a failed military coup
in 1992, is turning to the economy after overhauling Venezuela's
political structure with a new constitution, which required the
July elections to fill public offices on all levels.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-08-00 1702 </TRAILER>
