<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-08 17:30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New York party founder wants out of national Reform Party  </HEADLINE>
By ANNY KUO
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - A co-founder of the New York arm of the
Reform Party said Tuesday she wants to end the state's Independence
Party ties to the national party.
</P>
<P>
   Laureen Oliver, who was instrumental in the founding of the
Independence Party in 1991 and is a former state party chairwoman,
said it's ''very likely'' that the party will not endorse either
candidate seeking the national Reform Party's presidential
nomination at its state convention in September.
</P>
<P>
   Such a move could put Oliver at odds with another leader of the
state party, Lenora Fulani. The two have been allies in recent
months.
</P>
<P>
   Oliver, who is the Independence Party's secretary, said such a
move would essentially mean the New York party was disaffiliating
from the Reform Party. That is something the Minnesota arm of the
party, with the encouragement of Gov. Jesse Ventura, has already
done.
</P>
<P>
   Oliver's announcement came as Reform Party delegates were
gathering in Long Beach, Calif. for their national convention.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday night, members of the Monroe County faction of the
Independence Party - the largest in the state - voted against
supporting either Pat Buchanan or his lesser-known challenger John
Hagelin at the party's state convention.
</P>
<P>
   Oliver said the decision by Monroe County members has
''broad-based'' support in New York and predicted that position
would prevail at the September gathering.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's an extremely high chance that there won't be a Reform
Party candidate in New York,'' Oliver said. ''We're not obligated
legally to endorse their candidate.
</P>
<P>
   ''We just shortened the list. When the state convention opens in
September, it will be open to all presidential candidates -
Democrats, Republicans, Ralph Nader,'' she added.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Buchanan nor Hagelin are in line with the Independence
Party's ''centrist values,'' Oliver said.
</P>
<P>
   She said the national Reform Party's platform and organization
has drifted away from the New York affiliate's expectations.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's in effect a de facto vote to disaffiliate New York from
the Reform Party,'' she said of the possible outcome at the
September state convention.
</P>
<P>
   Oliver said she is so upset with the direction of the national
party that she has refused to attend the national convention.
</P>
<P>
   A major battle has erupted at the national convention between
Buchanan supporters and those of Hagelin, including some loyal to
party founder Ross Perot. Buchanan is battling an effort to have
him disqualified as a candidate for the party's nomination.
</P>
<P>
   New York's Independence Party also has its share of troubles. A
faction of the party headed by Fulani, a former leader of the
left-leaning New Alliance Party, first supported Buchanan then
switched to Hagelin.
</P>
<P>
   Sarah Lyons, a spokeswoman for the party's Democracy Coalition,
said both Fulani and party Chairman Frank MacKay are attending the
national convention. Lyons said about two dozen of the state
party's 31 delegates have gone to California.
</P>
<P>
   Oliver ''is just sending out a signal about which way Monroe
County is going to go'' at the New York convention, Lyons said.
''Hagelin is the strong favorite in New York.''
</P>
<P>
   Oliver said Fulani's faction is a ''very minor portion'' of the
state party organization.
</P>
<P>
   ''She's entitled to support what she pleases, but it doesn't
look the Independence Party is going to support her choice,''
Oliver said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
