<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-08 17:34 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lucent seeking chief operating officer to lead realigned company  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   MURRAY HILL, N.J. (AP) - Lucent Technologies is seeking a chief
operating officer as part of its reorganization to focus its
business on building the infrastructure for broadband and mobile
Internet services.
</P>
<P>
   The post has been vacant since October, when the two men who
held it jointly took other positions in the company.
</P>
<P>
   The company also announced Tuesday that Patricia Russo,
executive vice president and CEO of the service provider networks
group, has decided to leave the company.
</P>
<P>
   The moves are the latest in a series of recent restructuring
moves by the Murray Hill-based telecommunications giant, which
expects to shed two businesses and 50,000 employees by spring 2001.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are redefining Lucent to be the leader in building a
broadband and mobile Internet that will change the way people
communicate,'' chairman and chief executive officer Richard McGinn
said.
</P>
<P>
   In March, Lucent said it would spin off the enterprise networks
business, which sells voice and computer communication systems to
businesses. That division, and its 34,000 employees, are to be
separated by Sept. 30, spokesman Bill Price said.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Lucent said it would spin off its $4 billion-a-year
microelectronics business, which has 16,000 employees. That
business makes silicon chips and optoelectronic components such as
lasers used to build the telephone, wireless and Internet
communications systems Lucent sells.
</P>
<P>
   The spinoffs will leave Lucent with about 100,000 employees,
Price said.
</P>
<P>
   Lucent said last week it would split its optical networking
group into separate units focusing on long-distance and
metropolitan fiber optic networks. The networks carry digitized
voice, Internet and data traffic at high speeds on multiple
wavelengths, or channels, of light.
</P>
<P>
   Lucent's stock price, which was $84 in December, plunged to
$54.125 three weeks ago when company executives warned profits for
the next two quarters will be well below analysts' expectations.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, shares were down $2, or 5 percent, to close at
$40.25 on the New York Stock Exchange
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   Lucent Technologies: http://www.lucent.com
</P>
</TEXT>
