<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-08 17:37 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Eagleton poll puts finger in wind, comes up with taxes, economy  </HEADLINE>
By RALPH SIEGEL
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - It is still the economy stupid, and taxes,
too, that residents want to hear about most from their U.S. Senate
candidates.
</P>
<P>
   This is according to a poll done by the Eagleton Institute at
Rutgers University and analyzed by Eagleton professors who will be
monitoring the election campaign between Democrat Jon Corzine and
Republican U.S. Rep. Bob Franks.
</P>
<P>
   When 618 residents were asked to name the top problem a new
senator should address, 21 percent said taxes and 9 percent said
economic issues, according to the poll taken in early June. The
poll had a margin of error of 4.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Eagleton professor Ingrid Reed said the poll is being released
now because it took time to analyze the results and because voter
interest has been piqued by the GOP convention in Philadelphia and
the Democratic convention beginning Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ''The country's future cannot be addressed in generalities,''
Reed said. ''The candidate needs to know what people want answers
about.''
</P>
<P>
   The poll took two approaches.
</P>
<P>
   First, it asked voters to name their top concern without
providing a list of issues from which to choose. Reed said Eagleton
staff classified the spontaneous responses into issue groups.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, 6 percent wanted tax cuts, 6 percent wanted the
Social Security tax addressed, 5 percent identified property taxes
as their top concern, 1 percent mentioned other specific taxes and
3 percent said they were concerned about taxes in general. These
were merged to give taxes a response of 21 percent, the highest on
the poll.
</P>
<P>
   Another 9 percent mentioned as their top concern various points
about the economy, from jobs to inflation to the budget surplus to
high gasoline prices.
</P>
<P>
   Only 1 percent mentioned campaign finance - a key point of
Franks' attacks on Corzine for his excessive spending in the
primary campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ''I am really perplexed because of the apparent interest of the
voters in John McCain, where people would respond that they were
interested in him because of his position on campaign finance
reform. One guess would be that people don't see it affecting them
personally,'' Reed said.
</P>
<P>
   The second poll question listed nine issues and asked
respondents to identify whether they were ''very interested'' in
these subjects, allowing them to select more than one or
potentially all nine. In this round, 80 percent said they were very
interested in health issues, 78 percent in education and 72 percent
in Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   Corzine spokesman Tom Shea said the second poll question lines
up closely with Corzine's campaign message. As for economic
concerns, Shea said, ''I think that Jon feels very strongly that we
have to take advantage of this economic boom to invest in the
health care and education systems.''
</P>
<P>
   Franks campaign manager Charlie Smith said the poll shows that
Franks has been hitting the right economic points. ''Bob Franks has
said throughout this campaign season that he served four terms in
Congress committed to balancing the budget and cutting taxes,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   http://www.eagleton.rutgers.edu
</P>
<P>
   http://www.votecorzine.org
</P>
<P>
   http://www.bobfranks.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
