<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-08 17:39 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hillary Clinton: I want Lieberman to campaign with me  </HEADLINE>
By MARC HUMBERT
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - U.S. Senate candidate Hillary Rodham
Clinton, trying to court New York's crucial Jewish electorate, said
Tuesday she has already talked to Democratic vice presidential pick
Joseph Lieberman about campaigning with her.
</P>
<P>
   But Clinton's Republican rival, U.S. Rep. Rick Lazio, said ''if
the Clinton camp is counting on Joe Lieberman to push them over the
finish line, they are making a big mistake.''
</P>
<P>
   Lazio spokesman Dan McLagan said, ''Mrs. Clinton is trying to
hitch her rickety campaign wagon to Senator Lieberman's fine
reputation.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton borrowed a line that failed presidential candidate
Walter Mondale had used against his 1984 Democratic rival, Gary
Hart, to deride this year's Republican National Convention.
</P>
<P>
   ''After the Republican Convention of last week, a lot of people
were saying, 'Well, gee, where's the beef?' It's a pretty show and
everybody you know put on a good front, but what are their real
positions,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   The first lady said that with Al Gore at the top of the ticket
and Lieberman as his running mate, voters wouldn't be asking such
questions about the Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   ''We were talking about him coming to campaign for me here in
New York ... I think it's going to be fabulous,'' the first lady
said as she related a telephone discussion she and Lieberman had
Monday after his selection to become Gore's running mate.
</P>
<P>
   ''Here in New York, it's going to drive up the vice president's
numbers which will be great for the ticket,'' Clinton told Albany's
WROW-AM radio.
</P>
<P>
   ''I hope he'll be here, but I can't be greedy because he's got a
lot of ground to cover,'' she added.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, the first lady made it clear that she expected
Lieberman to continue to be supportive of her candidacy.
</P>
<P>
   ''He has stood up for me against some of the false accusations
that have come my way,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The first lady also said she expected the president to campaign
for her in New York heavily this fall.
</P>
<P>
   Polls have shown Clinton and Lazio running a tight Senate race
and with her falling below the 60 percent level among Jewish voters
that is traditionally thought necessary for a Democrat to win in
New York. Jews generally make up about 12 percent of the vote in
statewide races in New York.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Gore asked Lieberman to become the first Jew to ever
run for vice president on a major party ticket.
</P>
<P>
   The first lady has been fighting a perception that she is overly
sympathetic to the Palestinians and Lieberman has already tried to
aid her credibility on that front. In December, he accompanied the
first lady to a meeting with the Orthodox Union, which represents
Orthodox synagogues. Last month, Lieberman joined other Jewish
legislators in Washington defending her against an allegation that
she used an anti-Semitic obscenity in an argument in 1974.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman's friendship with the Clintons goes back to 1970, when
President Clinton - then a Yale Law student - campaigned for
Lieberman's state Senate campaign.
</P>
<P>
   While admitting she had differences with Lieberman on such
things as school vouchers - he favors them, while she does not -
the first lady said Tuesday that she was ''thrilled'' he had been
chosen by Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about Lieberman's criticism that her husband had engaged
in ''disgraceful'' conduct during the Monica Lewinsky sex scandal,
Clinton said, ''People will remember that when Joe said that, the
president said he agreed with him.''
</P>
<P>
   Lazio - noting the first lady's differences with Lieberman on
such things as school vouchers - said the first lady was ''miles
apart from'' the Connecticut senator on that and other issues.
</P>
<P>
   The first lady continued to duck questions about whether she
would debate her long-shot opponent for the Democratic Senate
nomination, Dr. Mark McMahon of Manhattan. She has called for a
series of debates against Lazio.
</P>
<P>
   While in Albany, the first lady picked up the expected
endorsement of the state's largest union, the New York State United
Teachers.
</P>
<P>
   Tony McCann, who teaches high school English in nearby Clifton
Park, said Lazio was ''a good man. It's nice to see him running,
but this bright lady is just leagues ahead of him. She's
scholarship material. He needs a lot of remedial help.''
</P>
<P>
   On the way to the teachers' union conference at an Albany hotel,
Clinton stopped her motorcade to chat with about 60 striking
Verizon Communications workers picketing outside the company's
office in downtown Albany.
</P>
<P>
   Later in the day, Clinton visited a Hasidic Jewish girl's school
in Rockland County where she was greeted by about 600 students,
their mothers and other relatives. She evoked Lieberman's name
several times.
</P>
<P>
   ''Perhaps you, as Jewish Americans, would take particular
pleasure in seeing Joe Lieberman given this great honor,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   While Clinton campaigned across New York, Lazio continued a
multi-day fund-raising trip that is taking him across the country
this week. On Tuesday, he was making stops in Denver and in
California.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
