<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-08 17:45 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> $Adv12-13  </HEADLINE>
By WILLIAM CONROY
<TEXT>
<P>
   TINTON FALLS, N.J. (AP) - At precisely 7:16 a.m. on a recent
Wednesday, when many people were just starting to wake up, travel
agency owner Stephen D. Weaver called the weekly meeting of LeTip
of Two Rivers/Red Bank to order in a banquet room at the Holiday
Inn of Tinton Falls.
</P>
<P>
   Members and guests scurried to their seats around tables
arranged in a rectangle and began standing up and telling each
other about their businesses.
</P>
<P>
   ''I hate getting up in the morning before 9 a.m.,'' Lynne Z.
Karinja confessed after the meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, the Tinton Falls-based certified public accountant
has been rising early once almost every week for five years - not
because she craves the breakfast buffet of fruit, bagels, coffee
and juice - but because LeTip is worth it for her business, she
said.
</P>
<P>
   LeTip is not the only business group that brings business people
together on a regular basis. Networking happens on virtually a
daily basis in a variety of other organizations in Monmouth and
Ocean counties, and entrepreneurs say it provides a big boost to
their business.
</P>
<P>
   In the age of the Internet, small business owners have a wealth
of options - including Web sites, e-mail and faxes - to promote
themselves, but they say there still is no substitute for
face-to-face contact.
</P>
<P>
   ''Fortunately, the computer hasn't displaced people
completely,'' said Milton Leontiades, dean of the Rutgers
University School of Business in Camden. ''Face-to-face contact is
still the most effective way to sell.''
</P>
<P>
   Pat G. Angelastro, a native of Bergen County who bought the
Drifting Sands Oceanfront Hotel in Ship Bottom last February, said
networking through local organizations is a necessity for him.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's one of the things I've been trying to do to get myself
and the name of the company out there to the community,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Angelastro, 30, joined the Southern Ocean County Chamber of
Commerce and the Long Beach Island Rotary Club after buying his
hotel. Membership in both organizations has already resulted in
referrals and additional bookings, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm sure there is probably a blend of reasons in everybody's
membership,'' said Jeanne DiPaola, executive director of the
Southern Ocean County Chamber of Commerce, which has about 550
members. ''New businesses are very eager to join the chamber
because it gives their businesses credibility.''
</P>
<P>
   J. Wandres, an Aberdeen-based writer and public relations
consultant, was one of 42 people who paid $25 to display his wares
at a recent ''business showcase'' sponsored by the Monmouth-Ocean
Development Council and the Jersey Shore Public Relations and
Advertising Association.
</P>
<P>
   No one closes a deal at such get-togethers, said Wandres. But
you may make some business contacts, swap business cards and try to
develop a business relationship in the future, he explained.
</P>
<P>
   Wandres said he met a graphic designer, Howard Levy, five years
ago through the public relations and advertising association. The
contact has resulted in several projects for Wandres over the
years, either through referrals or joint efforts with Levy, said
Wandres. He is currently working on three projects with the
graphics designer.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps no group has perfected the art of business networking as
well as LeTip International. The organization is the purest, most
stripped-down form of a networking organization that a business
owner or manager can find.
</P>
<P>
   As its name suggests, members of the group meet to swap business
tips or leads. A tip is defined as a company or a person who is
interested in a specific service or product offered by a LeTip
member and who expects a call from that member.
</P>
<P>
   LeTip member Bill Cowley said he and his brother, Drew, closely
track where their business comes from at Cowley's Pest Control in
Neptune City. They each belong to a different LeTip chapter and
said they can trace $13,000 worth of business this year back to
leads they've received from LeTip contacts.
</P>
<P>
   One of the ways that LeTip differs from other business groups is
that the membership is restricted to one of each kind of business,
so members do not compete with each other, said Weaver, president
of LeTip of Two Rivers/Red Bank and owner of Carlson Wagonlit
Travel in Tinton Falls. The group has 31 members.
</P>
<P>
   ''I look at it as an extension of my sales force,'' Weaver said.
''These people are working for me.''
</P>
<P>
   The meeting moves along with military-like precision, although
there is a lot of kidding back and forth among the members. Once
each month, a member visits another member's business, and at this
meeting they are reporting on those visits. There is a 30-second
time limit on those reports, and Weaver enforces it with a bell.
</P>
<P>
   Karinja, who co-owns the Tinton Falls-based accounting firm
Liska, Karinja &AMP; Associates LLC, said one of the things she likes
about LeTip is that it's time-efficient networking. As a business
owner and mother of two children, she said she has to be selective
about how she uses her time.
</P>
<P>
   LeTip was founded in 1978 in San Diego. Members receive small
rewards (such as $2 if they pass four or more tips to other
members) or pay small fines ($1 for bringing no tips to a meeting,
for example).
</P>
<P>
   The organization is not to everyone's taste, Karinja said. Over
the past few years, the Two Rivers group has had a core of about 15
members, but the others change, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Membership costs $350 in the first year, plus a $95 payment
quarterly, then $200 a year after that, plus the $95 quarterly
payment.
</P>
<P>
   End Adv12-13
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-08-08-00 1745 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
