<DOCNO> APW20000808.0122 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-08 17:47 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> State may let compulsive gamblers ban themselves from casinos  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN CURRAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTIC CITY, N.J. (AP) - Compulsive gamblers who can't resist
the lure of clinking slot machines and spinning roulette wheels may
soon get a new tool to help themselves.
</P>
<P>
   The state of New Jersey, which maintains a list of mobsters,
cheats and others who are banned from entering casinos, is
proposing a ''self-exclusion'' program that would allow problem
gamblers to ban themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Under it, gamblers could register with the state and provide a
photograph of themselves to casinos, which would then be required
to deny them access to games, credit, complimentary items,
check-cashing privileges, players club perks, direct-mail
promotions and other benefits.
</P>
<P>
   The initiative, announced Monday by the state Division of Gaming
Enforcement, mirrors similar efforts in Connecticut, Missouri,
Michigan and Louisiana.
</P>
<P>
   It still must be approved by the state Casino Control Commission
to take effect.
</P>
<P>
   One casino gambling critic called the proposal window dressing,
aimed at masking the fact that casinos depend on gambling addicts
for their profits.
</P>
<P>
   ''I won't slam any recognition by casinos that there's a
problem, but if this is the best they can do for a diseased person,
telling them 'It's going to rely on you to treat yourself,' then
the problem will persist,'' said the Rev. Tom Grey, executive
director of the National Coalition Against Gambling Expansion.
''Don't forget, their profitability comes from people who are
pathological gamblers.''
</P>
<P>
   An estimated 16 million Americans have experienced gambling
problems at some point in their lives, according to the National
Research Council.
</P>
<P>
   The director of the New Jersey Division of Gaming Enforcement,
J.P. Suarez, said anyone on the list discovered in a casino would
be escorted off by security guards, Suarez said.
</P>
<P>
   They would not face criminal sanctions, however, and the ban
would not be permanent. A person could have his name removed from
the list by formally requesting it and waiting 30 days, Suarez
said.
</P>
<P>
   Casinos, meanwhile, could face cash penalties for violating the
ban, Suarez said.
</P>
<P>
   The Division of Gaming Enforcement is in discussions with the
state attorney general's office about the possibility of forcing
casinos and excluded gamblers to forfeit money won or lost by a
person while on the self exclusion list, Suarez said.
</P>
<P>
   No regulation has been proposed for that yet, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Edward Looney, executive director of the Council on Compulsive
Gambling of New Jersey, applauded the self-exclusion proposal
Tuesday. He said many recovering gamblers reported relapses after
receiving promotional literature or invitations from casinos in the
mail.
</P>
<P>
   ''There are not going to be thousands and thousands of people
signing up for this. These programs have been in place elsewhere
and the numbers haven't been large. But the ones who are serious
about getting rid of the temptations, they will go along with it,''
Looney said.
</P>
<P>
   Grey, an anti-casino crusader who travels the country organizing
opposition to ballot referendums on casino gambling, said the
proposal is ''a day late and a dollar short.''
</P>
<P>
   ''How long have you had casinos there? Twenty years? Now, 20
years down the road, they've discovered self-exclusion? When they
start moving the ATMs and credit offices off the casino floors,
I'll take them seriously,'' Grey said.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Goodman, executive director of the nonprofit U.S.
Gambling Research Institute in Northampton, Mass., called the
program a step in the right direction but questioned whether it
would have much impact on problem gamblers, who by their nature do
not believe they have a problem.
</P>
<P>
   ''They need a program like this for legislators, who seem to
compulsively turn to gambling every time they have a fiscal
problem,'' said Goodman, author of ''The Luck Business,'' a book
about gambling. ''If they could get legislators to sign onto it,
saying they won't turn to casinos when they have a fiscal problem,
that would be even better.''
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   On the Web:
</P>
<P>
   Council on Compulsive Gambling of New Jersey:
www.800gambler.org.
</P>
<P>
   American Gaming Association: www.americangaming.org
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-08-08-00 1747 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000808.0123 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-08 17:53 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jogger in critical condition after being struck by lightning  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   COLTS NECK, N.J. (AP) - A Monmouth County jogger was in critical
but stable condition Tuesday, a day after being struck by lightning
during a severe thunderstorm that felled trees, downed power lines
and crushed several cars.
</P>
<P>
   Raul Damas, 57, of Middletown, saw the black clouds and began to
jog back home when he was struck by lightning, police said. A
neighbor found him unconscious and bleeding on the side of a road
about 6:30 p.m., then called police. He was taken to Riverview
Medical Center in Red Bank.
</P>
<P>
   ''His clothes were torn and singed and he had a mark on his
neck,'' Police Sgt. William Best told The Star-Ledger of Newark for
Tuesday's edition.
</P>
<P>
   ''He had a Walkman radio ... it was broken open and the circuit
board was melted.''
</P>
<P>
   Reports of funnel clouds prompted the National Weather Service
Tuesday to investigate whether a tornado touched down in Colts
Neck. Meteorologist Jim Poirier said preliminary reports indicate
the storm damage was caused by straight line winds, rather than a
tornado.
</P>
<P>
   Straight line winds, during a severe storm, spread out
horizontally and form a straight line along the ground. He
estimated that winds reached at least 60 miles per hour.
</P>
<P>
   The thunderstorm also snapped six telephone poles in Hopewell
Township, Mercer County, along Route 518, said Police Chief Michael
Chipowski.
</P>
<P>
   Ron Morano, a spokesman for GPU Energy, said 1,700 customers in
central New Jersey lost power about 6 p.m. Monday. At least 800 of
those customers were in Colts Neck, Freehold and Jamesburg. Power
was restored to all customers by 9 a.m. Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Monmouth County Emergency Management Coordinator Harry Conover
told the Asbury Park Press that he believed the area was hit by a
tornado.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're just incredibly lucky that no one was hurt and there was
no substantial property damage,'' Conover said.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Maddox, of Marlboro, told the newspaper that he witnessed
a still summer sky produce intense and multidirectional winds in a
matter of seconds.
</P>
<P>
   ''There were two small funnels going from west to east right
over my house,'' he said, adding that 90-foot trees were uprooted
and one of them flattened his son's car. ''I'll have firewood for
the next 20 years.''
</P>
<P>
   ''There may have been a funnel cloud, which is a rotating column
of air not in contact with the ground,'' Poirier said, ''but the
damage in Colts Neck was done by the straight line winds.''
Tornados are funnel clouds that actually touch ground.
</P>
<P>
   The storm developed in Bucks County, Pa., and passed through
northern Mercer, southern Somerset, southern Middlesex and Monmouth
counties between 5 and 6:30 p.m. Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Verizon spokeswoman Soraya Rodriguez said between 75 and 100
customers remained without phone service Tuesday night after
Monday's storm downed a phone line on School Road East in Colts
Neck.
</P>
<P>
   She said workers were scheduled to restore the line by early
Wednesday evening.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-08-08-00 1753 </TRAILER>
