<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-08 17:57 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Historic home to join women's rights national park  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) - President Clinton signed legislation on
Tuesday allowing the house where the first women's rights
convention was planned to become part of the Women's Rights
National Historical Park.
</P>
<P>
   The move allows the National Park Service to acquire Hunt House
in Waterloo, N.Y. - opening it up for public tours and special
events along with the rest of the park.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan, a Democrat, and Rep. Thomas
Reynolds, a Republican, sponsored the bill. Reynolds' western New
York district contains Hunt House.
</P>
<P>
   It was at a tea hosted by Richard and Jane Hunt in July 1848
that Elizabeth Cady Stanton, Lucretia Mott and other early women's
rights activists hatched the idea of holding a women's rights
convention. Following the meeting, the women drafted the
groundbreaking Declaration of Sentiments. That manifesto was
presented at the Women's Rights Convention in Seneca Falls, N.Y.
later that month.
</P>
<P>
   The house was privately owned until 1999 when the National Trust
for Historic Preservation purchased it. They have been leasing it
to the Park Service at no cost.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Hunt House is a place of enormous historic significance
and deserves to be in the National Park System,'' National Trust
President Richard Moe said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The trust plans to provide any sale proceeds to the restoration
effort for the home.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
