<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-08 18:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pataki signs bill barring Con Ed from passing outage costs to customers </HEADLINE>
By ANNY KUO
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - Consolidated Edison will be barred from
charging customers with costs related to the outage at its Indian
Point 2 nuclear power plant under a bill signed into law by Gov.
George Pataki Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Under the legislation, the state Public Service Commission is
prohibited from allowing the utility to apply replacement costs
incurred since the Feb. 15 outage to its utility base or otherwise
pass through charges to ratepayers.
</P>
<P>
   The PSC will also be required to order Con Ed to refund any
outage-related costs charged to ratepayers.
</P>
<P>
   ''Con Ed must be held accountable for its failures, which
clearly led to this shutdown,'' Pataki said. ''New Yorkers should
not be forced to pay for Con Ed's mistakes.''
</P>
<P>
   Con Ed spokesman Joseph Petta said the utility plans to
challenge the matter in court.
</P>
<P>
   ''In passing unlawful legislation, the state sends a message to
all of its citizens and corporations that politics overrides sound
public policy,'' Petta said. ''We are confident that the courts
will recognize that this bill is unconstitutional.''
</P>
<P>
   It is costing the utility about $600,000 a day to buy
replacement electricity, and Petta said that would add about $2 a
month to the typical electric bill of a residential customer.
</P>
<P>
   A leak in a tube at the plant carrying radioactive water
resulted in the release of a minute amount of radioactive steam
into the atmosphere. There was no measurable effect on the
environment and no one was injured, but it resulted in the first
alert in the 26-year history of the Westchester County plant.
</P>
<P>
   A Nuclear Regulatory Commission report on the outage concluded
that if Con Ed had done a more thorough job, it would have been
able to predict ''an increased probability of tube leakage or
rupture'' by June 2000.
</P>
<P>
   According to the PSC, refunds to ratepayers are expected to
total about $162 million and will appear in September bills.
Ratepayers will also not be charged approximately $60 million in
replacement costs that Con Ed is expected to spend until defective
steam generators are replaced.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier Tuesday, state Assembly Speaker Sheldon Silver sent a
letter to Pataki urging the governor to sign the legislation into
law. Silver applauded Pataki's move later in the day.
</P>
<P>
   ''The governor's approval is clearly a step in the right
direction toward reducing soaring electricity costs for millions of
New Yorkers,'' Silver said.
</P>
<P>
   The bill's Senate sponsor, Republican Guy Velella of the Bronx,
said the new law ''will send a swift, severe and certain message to
Con Ed - you can't put profits ahead of people.''
</P>
<P>
   The law will remain in effect until the end of the outage or
until all defective steam generation equipment at the facility has
been replaced, whichever happens later.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-08-08-00 1804 </TRAILER>
