<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Senators Ready for Leadership Jobs  </HEADLINE>
By CLAUDE R. MARX
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- With the encouragement of the Senate's top
Republican, two senators could stroll into leadership jobs with no
opposition.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Rick Santorum of Pennsylvania is running for chairman of
the Republican Conference, the No. 3 leadership spot, and Sen. Kay
Bailey Hutchison of Texas is running for conference secretary, the
No. 4 position.
</P>
<P>
   They had planned to compete for conference secretary, but the
death last month of Sen. Paul Coverdell, R-Ga., opened the race for
conference chairman. Coverdell had announced plans to run for
chairman to replace Sen. Connie Mack, R-Fla., who is not seeking
re-election. Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., persuaded
Santorum and Hutchison to avoid a potentially divisive race.
</P>
<P>
   Santorum has said that his youth, ideology and geography are his
best assets for the leadership. A strong conservative, he has been
active on such issues as welfare reform and the fight to ban the
procedure that opponents call ''partial-birth'' abortions.
</P>
<P>
   Hutchison's chief of staff, David DiRita, said the secretary
spot is a good match for her talents.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a natural development to formally join the leadership
since she's been working closely with the majority leader in
getting our message out,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Hutchison, a former television reporter, is a frequent party
spokeswoman on such issues as tax reform and welfare reform.
</P>
<P>
   Sens. Bill Frist, R-Tenn., and Chuck Hagel, R-Neb., are also
considering running for leadership spots but their spokesmen said
Tuesday they had not made any final decisions.
</P>
<P>
   The leadership races are scheduled for December.
</P>
<P>
   The conference chairman helps the majority leader and assistant
majority leader set the agenda and runs conference meetings, while
the conference secretary coordinates efforts among Senate
Republicans to devise communications strategy and policy positions.
</P>
<P>
   Both Hutchison and Santorum, meanwhile, are running for
re-election this year.
</P>
<P>
   Hutchison is heavily favored over Gene Kelly, a retired military
attorney who has lost six previous statewide races, while Santorum,
challenged by U.S. Rep. Ron Klink, D-Pa., has a 20-point lead
according to a Keystone Poll released last month.
</P>
<P>
   Santorum would be the only northeasterner and the first
Pennsylvanian in the GOP leadership since the late Sen. Hugh Scott
was minority leader from 1969 to 1977.
</P>
<P>
   Hutchison would be the first woman in the GOP leadership and the
first Texan to be a party leader since Sen. Lyndon B. Johnson was
the Democratic leader in the 1950s.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   Hutchison: http://www.senate.gov/(tilde)hutchison
</P>
<P>
   Santorum: http://www.senate.gov/(tilde)santorum
</P>
</TEXT>
