<HEADLINE> Concorde Pilot Buried in France  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   VILLARS-COLMARS, France (AP) -- About 500 mourners gathered in
this village Tuesday to bury the pilot of the Concorde plane that
crashed last month, as Air France promised that victims' families
would receive compensation.
</P>
<P>
   Pilot Christian Marty was among 113 people killed when the
luxury jet crashed outside Paris shortly after takeoff on July 25.
</P>
<P>
   Friends and family, including Marty's widow and two children,
attended the open-air Mass held at a children's playground in the
main square of Villars-Colmars. Marty's widow is a native of the
region in southeast France.
</P>
<P>
   Marty was credited for trying to steer the plane toward a small
airstrip and away from populated areas as its engines spewed out
fire seconds into takeoff. The plane crashed into a hotel in a
rural area.
</P>
<P>
   Among those at the funeral was Air France President Jean-Cyril
Spinetta.
</P>
<P>
   The airline's chief financial officer, Philippe Calavia, told
reporters that the company's insurers would compensate the families
of the crash victims in accordance with international laws. But he
did not specify the sums that would be involved.
</P>
<P>
   He said the carrier's priority has been ''moral and financial
aid to families of victims,'' not its own financial concerns in the
wake of the crash.
</P>
<P>
   Calavia said the suspension of Concorde flights following the
crash has not caused Air France a significant loss in income
because the luxury fleet is only ''slightly profitable.''
Passengers are not shying away from Air France since the crash, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the airline may have to devise flight alternatives if the
Concorde remains grounded, as the French Transportation Ministry
ordered while investigators try to figure out the cause of the
crash.
</P>
<P>
   ''What I can say is that if the fleet remains grounded, we'll
have to imagine a new program concerning flights on North Atlantic
routes,'' Calavia said. ''There are passengers using the Concorde,
and they won't disappear.''
</P>
<P>
   He added that it is ''much too early'' to speculate about the
future of the Concorde.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-08-00 1808 </TRAILER>
