<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-08 18:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Envoy To Visit North Korea  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEOUL, South Korea (AP) -- A U.S. envoy will visit North Korea
this week to urge the isolated communist country to clear its
record on terrorism before the outside world can embrace it as a
good neighbor, U.S. officials said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Sheehan, U.S. coordinator for counter-terrorism, is
leading a delegation that will hold talks in Pyongyang, the North
Korean capital, on Wednesday and Thursday, the officials said.
</P>
<P>
   In Seoul, U.S. diplomats said Sheehan will explain the steps the
North must take to be considered for removal from the U.S. list of
state sponsors for terrorism.
</P>
<P>
   State Department spokesman Richard Boucher in Washington
confirmed the trip, saying that the last round of talks between the
United States and North Korea on terrorism took place in New York
in March.
</P>
<P>
   North Korea is one of seven countries branded by the U.S. State
Department as a sponsor of terrorism. Under U.S. law, this bars all
but humanitarian aid to the Pyongyang government and rules out bank
loans from international financial organizations, which are heavily
influenced by Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Seeking reconciliation with North Korea, South Korea is trying
to help the impoverished North work more closely with the
international finance system by winning membership in such
institutions as the Asian Development Bank.
</P>
<P>
   But the United States and Japan ruled out even observer status
in the bank unless the North's hard-line leaders address
international fears that the country sponsors terrorism.
</P>
<P>
   Sheehan first took up the subject in talks with North Korean
Vice Foreign Minister Kim Gye Gwan in New York in March.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. officials reportedly demand that North Korea publicly
renounce terrorism and expel all terrorism suspects before it can
be considered for removal from their list.
</P>
<P>
   Pyongyang was put on the terrorism list because of involvement
in the midair bombing of a South Korean airliner near Burma, now
Myanmar, in 1987. All 115 people on board the Korean Air plane
died.
</P>
<P>
   North Korea has normalized ties with Italy, Australia and the
Philippines this year in gestures apparently aimed at easing
international concerns over the country and facilitating outside
economic aid.
</P>
<P>
   The North also is pursuing better relations with the United
States and Japan. Its leader, Kim Jong Il, held an unprecedented
summit in June with South Korean President Kim Dae-jung.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-08-00 1823 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000808.0131 </DOCNO>
