<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-08 18:36 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russian Cops Report Foiled Murder  </HEADLINE>
By ANGELA CHARLTON
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW (AP) -- Security officials said Tuesday they had foiled an
attempt to assassinate a prominent governor over an apparent
property dispute in the aluminum industry -- one of the most
lucrative and allegedly crime-ridden sectors of the economy.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Security Service said the key suspects were arrested
and accused of planning to poison Aman Tuleyev, a presidential
candidate who came in fourth in the March election.
</P>
<P>
   Tuleyev, governor of the Kemerovo region in western Siberia,
said in a statement that the plot appeared linked to attempts to
gain control of metallurgy factories in his province.
</P>
<P>
   Russian news reports suggested a possible link to organized
crime and said Tuleyev's assassins had been promised $700,000 for
the hit.
</P>
<P>
   The security service confirmed that suspects had been arrested
in raids Monday in Moscow and Novosibirsk in Siberia, but declined
to give any details, including why Tuleyev may have been targeted.
</P>
<P>
   While contract killings involving disputes over control of
businesses and public funds are commonplace in Russia, they rarely
involve such prominent figures.
</P>
<P>
   ''When I took over the region three years ago, it was in the
hands of criminal mobs,'' Tuleyev said on Russia's RTR television
Tuesday night. ''Professional criminals sat on the boards of
directors at numerous companies.''
</P>
<P>
   Tuleyev mentioned the Kuznetsk Metallurgical Combine, the
Novokuznetsk Aluminum Plant and some coal mines. The plants had
been owned by the MIKOM conglomerate until Tuleyev's administration
declared them bankrupt earlier this year, and assigned
representatives from the influential Siberian Aluminum conglomerate
to take over.
</P>
<P>
   Siberian Aluminum is part of the financial empire run by Roman
Abramovich, a secretive tycoon believed to have close links to the
Kremlin.
</P>
<P>
   The director of MIKOM, Mikhail Zhivilo, was reported missing
Tuesday, the Interfax news agency said. Police searched MIKOM's
offices in Moscow as part of the probe into the plot against
Tuleyev, the report said.
</P>
<P>
   Tuleyev and MIKOM had clashed frequently, and the governor once
sent police into the Kuznetsk's steel mill to oust a top manager.
MIKOM offices were not answering the phones Tuesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-08-00 1836 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000808.0132 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-08 18:37 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> By MATTHEW DALY  </HEADLINE>
By MATTHEW DALY
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) - U.S. Sen. Joseph Lieberman, the new
Democratic nominee for vice president, has won praise nationally as
a moderate willing to reach across party lines.
</P>
<P>
   But back in Connecticut, his Republican Senate opponent attacked
Lieberman as a ''chameleon'' whose conservative talk masks a
liberal voting record.
</P>
<P>
   Waterbury Mayor Philip Giordano, who is challenging Lieberman
for a U.S. Senate seat, denounced the two-term senator as ''a very
extreme liberal'' whose views do not represent the state.
</P>
<P>
   ''When it really counts, Lieberman sticks with his party,''
Giordano said, attacking Lieberman's record on Social Security,
crime, taxes and a host of other issues.
</P>
<P>
   At a press conference at the Legislative Office Building Tuesday
- just minutes before Lieberman officially joined the Democratic
ticket in Nashville - Giordano criticized dozens of votes Lieberman
has made in his 12-year Senate career.
</P>
<P>
   Giordano handed out a 40-page report entitled ''The Worst of
Senator Joseph Lieberman,'' in which he slammed Lieberman for votes
he said failed to protect seniors, funded pornography and even left
children open to attack by pedophiles. Giordano denied he was
making personal attacks and said he was merely exposing Lieberman's
true record.
</P>
<P>
   ''Records are a matter of target, if you will,'' Giordano said,
adding that his own service as Waterbury mayor and state
representative is also open to scrutiny.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman in Lieberman's Senate office declined to comment
Tuesday, but a spokesman for the Gore-Lieberman ticket said from
Nashville that Giordano's claims were off base. ''I think it's
pretty clear, when you hear Democrats and Republicans unanimously
praising Joe Lieberman as a moderate, independent voice and a man
of integrity, no matter how much paper you produce (attacking him),
you are screaming into the wind.''
</P>
<P>
   Democratic state Chairman Edward L. Marcus ridiculed Giordano's
attack as the act of a ''desperate'' man, noting that Giordano
trailed Lieberman by 57 percentage points in a recent poll.
</P>
<P>
   ''With this kind of campaign it's no wonder the city of
Waterbury is in the shape that it's in,'' Marcus said.
</P>
<P>
   One of the more sensational charges made by Giordano involved a
1990 vote he said showed Lieberman was ''opposed to protecting
children from pedophiles.'' The bill involved organizations in
Washington, D.C., that were seeking to bar ''any person convicted
of or charged with a sexual offense involving a minor from coaching
or teaching,'' Giordano's memo said. But when asked what
organizations, specifically, were targeted in the legislation,
Giordano said he did not know.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he was accusing Lieberman of supporting pedophiles,
Giordano said no, but added, ''He certainly had an opportunity to
protect children from pedophiles and he didn't do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Giordano also attacked Lieberman for supporting funding for the
National Endowment for the Arts, even though the agency has
sponsored works that some consider obscene or pornographic, and
criticized Lieberman for voting to increase the federal gas tax and
opposing bills to eliminate the so-called marriage penalty,
eliminate estate taxes for the wealthy and outlaw flag burning.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
