<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-08 18:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Residents watch Lieberman officially accept Gore's VP offer  </HEADLINE>
By JUDITH FORMAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) - Joseph Lieberman's voice on Tuesday
boomed from every corner of the Hartford restaurant where he once
celebrated a national college basketball title.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman got the official vice presidential nod from Al Gore in
front of a nation. But at Coach's restaurant, the New Haven senator
spoke to just a few lunchtime stragglers watching the televisions
suspended from the ceiling.
</P>
<P>
   ''He's a good guy, a straight shooter,'' said Mark Dumond, a
salesman from Colchester, who was eating at the bar during his
lunch hour. ''I think it'll benefit Connecticut. He's going to try
to bring stuff back to the state.''
</P>
<P>
   Coach's is a popular hangout for University of Connecticut
basketball fans and owned by men's coach Jim Calhoun. Lieberman was
there in 1999 when the Huskies beat Duke for the National
Collegiate Athletic Association title.
</P>
<P>
   Around the corner at Max Downtown, the lunchtime crowd was
largely indifferent to the news from Nashville, Tenn. But three
Hartford businessmen said they are glad Lieberman's on the ticket -
even though they are skeptical of Gore.
</P>
<P>
   ''Joe Lieberman has a toughness that's really based on integrity
and belief,'' said Peter Aldridge of Wethersfield. ''Of all the
politicians I've seen, I believe he belongs up there. I would
absolutely put Joe Lieberman on an international stage.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Lieberman is one of the few Democrats he's ever voted
for, Peter Barrett of East Hampton said he still remains ''not a
fan of Al Gore's.''
</P>
<P>
   ''You can't be that close to what Clinton is all about and not
be tainted in some way,'' Barrett said.
</P>
<P>
   A group of about 35 rabbis and community leaders gathered at the
Jewish Federation's West Hartford office to watch the first Jew to
officially join a major-party ticket.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's a great sense of hope,'' said Ethan Felson, executive
director of the Jewish Community Relations Council of the Jewish
Federation of Greater Hartford. ''This symbolizes that any American
- including an American Jew - can do and be anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Felson said he is confident that Gore chose Lieberman for his
merits, not his religion. And, Felson said, the public won't be
swayed by Lieberman's Judaism.
</P>
<P>
   ''I believe in my heart that people will view this candidacy on
the merits just as they would any other candidate,'' Felson said.
</P>
<P>
   At the state Legislative Office Building, lawmakers watched the
televised announcement in their offices. Senate President Pro
Tempore Kevin B. Sullivan took in the speeches as he lunched on
yogurt and a sandwich.
</P>
<P>
   ''I was struck by how good they looked together,'' said the West
Hartford Democrat. ''They look like they fit together. They've been
friends for a very long while.''
</P>
<P>
   In Stamford, the city where Lieberman grew up, there is genuine
excitement about him making it to the No. 2 spot on the Democratic
ticket.
</P>
<P>
   But Lieberman's hometown boy status wasn't enough to change some
voters' minds who watched the announcement at a local sports bar
owned by another famous Stamford native, New York Mets manager
Bobby Valentine.
</P>
<P>
   ''I respect Lieberman because he's stood his ground and turned
against some (traditional) Democratic thoughts,'' said Jeff
LaMonica, a landscape designer from Stamford who plans to vote
Republican. ''He was the first one to chastise Clinton for the
stuff that happened with Monica. God bless him.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
