<HEADLINE> Two Philadelphia brothers charged in stolen credit card scam  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   ATLANTIC CITY, N.J. (AP) - Two brothers suspected of running a
stolen credit card ring that preyed on movie theater patrons were
captured outside a casino, authorities said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Cherode Spence, 39, and Sidney Spence, 34, both of Philadelphia,
had been wanted for months in connection with the theft of credit
cards when they were spotted Monday outside Caesars Atlantic City
Hotel Casino, according to state Division of Gaming Enforcement
officials.
</P>
<P>
   State Police assigned to the division arrested the two, who had
been identified previously by 17 women who participated in credit
card scams with them, Gaming Enforcement spokeswoman Katherine
Lyons said.
</P>
<P>
   The two would sneak around in darkened movie theaters, taking
the purses of middle-aged women while the victims were watching
movies and then removing credit cards before returning the purse,
Lyons said.
</P>
<P>
   ''They would only take the credit card. They wouldn't take
anything else, so it took a while for people to notice,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The brothers would then create fake identifications to match the
credit cards and enlist women to pose as the owners of the cards,
appearing at casinos to obtain cash advances of between $500 and
$2,000, according to Attorney General John J. Farmer Jr.
</P>
<P>
   The Spences, who were both wanted on bench warrants for failing
to appear on similar charges here in 1999, were each charged with
one count of theft by deception and one count of using a stolen
credit card. More charges are expected, Lyons said.
</P>
<P>
   Also arrested were Tameka Chante Nash, 26, and Sharon Vidra, 20,
both of Philadelphia. They face the same charges.
</P>
<P>
   The Spences and Nash were being held on $50,000 bail Tuesday.
Vidra was being held on $40,000 bail.
</P>
</TEXT>
