<HEADLINE> Congress Concerned With Census  </HEADLINE>
By GENARO C. ARMAS
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Congressional investigators are reviewing
Census Bureau memos and e-mails following allegations from a House
Republican that the agency is not cooperating fully in monitoring
the count.
</P>
<P>
   It has prompted concerns from Census officials and Rep. Carolyn
Maloney, D-N.Y., ranking member of the House Government Reform
Committee's census panel, that the privacy of e-mail messages of
thousands of Census employees may be invaded.
</P>
<P>
   In May, Rep. Dan Miller, R-Fla., produced an e-mail from an
unidentified Los Angeles-area census manager instructing
lower-ranking officials not to provide certain daily progress
reports to the General Accounting Office, Congress' investigative
arm. The GAO is helping oversee the once-a-decade count.
</P>
<P>
   Census director Kenneth Prewitt has said there is no policy to
deny GAO any information. Census officials also said that GAO
officials have access to such information through agency computers,
and that such information is also offered by regional-level
management to the GAO.
</P>
<P>
   In a follow-up letter to Prewitt on July 20, GAO associate
director J. Christopher Mihm requested copies of ''any and all
correspondence, memoranda, e-mail messages, and any other form of
communication between officers or employers of the Census Bureau''
concerning GAO or any other oversight body's access to Census data.
</P>
<P>
   Census officials said Tuesday that the request could possibly
entail information from 14,000 computers in 520 offices and more
than 15,000 e-mail accounts.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are in the early stages of a design process for the
study,'' said GAO spokesman Jeff Nelligan. ''We are working closely
with the congressional staffs in doing so.''
</P>
<P>
   Nelligan said the investigation was launched after letters from
Miller, chairman of the census subcommittee, and Maloney. But
Maloney's office said her only concern was with the Los Angeles
incident and not other offices.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's almost like the Republicans think that getting an
accurate census should be considered a crime and those who are
working to count Americans should have their privacy invaded on a
whim. It is outrageous and I hope that the GAO will refuse to
proceed,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have no idea of the scope, magnitude, cost or operational
burden that this would impose except to say that it's massive,''
Census spokesman Steve Jost said.
</P>
<P>
   ''We think it's important to know whether or not the Census
Bureau has intended to fully cooperate with oversight committees,''
Miller's spokesman Chip Walker said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-08-00 1854 </TRAILER>
