<HEADLINE> 5 Civilians Win 'Fantasy Career'  </HEADLINE>
By ROBERT BURNS
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- A stint in the military has never been like
this: Five civilians who competed for ''fantasy careers'' in the
military won the right to spend a few days living the role of
soldier, sailor or airman.
</P>
<P>
   The winners are a middle-aged salesman, a teen-age student, a
United Airlines service representative, an eighth-grade teacher and
a 22-year-old woman attracted to the idea of a career in the Coast
Guard.
</P>
<P>
   They were selected from among 3,355 who submitted essays in a
gimmick contest developed by the Yahoo! Internet company. The
Pentagon approved it as a way to boost recruitment and raise
awareness of the military among ''influencers'' -- such as teachers,
who influence young people's career choices.
</P>
<P>
   Contestants had to be U.S. residents 18 or older, complete an
entry form, submit a resume and answer a simple essay question
through Yahoo! It is part of the Pentagon's effort to make more use
of the Internet for recruiting and advertising.
</P>
<P>
   Rosalyn-Sue Smith, 18, of Marietta, Ga., was chosen by the Army
to spend several days in September at Fort Rucker, Ala. She will
train with an Apache helicopter pilot and do a tandem parachute
jump with the Army's Golden Knights.
</P>
<P>
   Smith, a student at Kennesaw State University north of Marietta,
wrote in her winning essay, ''Since I was a young girl, the
tradition, history and brotherhood that come along with the right
to be called an American soldier have captivated and inspired me.''
</P>
<P>
   The Air Force chose Dale E. Zimmerman, 22, of Junction City,
Ore., a student at Embry-Riddle Aeronautical University.
</P>
<P>
   He says he wants to apply for Air Force officer training school
to become a pilot. His ''fantasy career'' will be two days at
Tyndall Air Force Base, near Panama City, Fla., an honorary jet
pilot in training.
</P>
<P>
   ''Being blessed with the opportunity to spend a day shadowing an
F-15 pilot will give me a taste of what is to come,'' he wrote in
his winning essay. ''It will at least hold me over until I can have
the honor of strapping into my own jet every day.''
</P>
<P>
   The Marine Corps chose Richard A. Castanet, 47, of Richmond,
Va., who will spend several days in September at the Basic School
at Quantico, Va., and at Parris Island, S.C., where new recruits
are trained.
</P>
<P>
   Asked what he looked forward to most, Castanet said, ''Being
with Marines (and) being a Marine.''
</P>
<P>
   The Navy selected Joseph W. Blondo, 31, of Budd Lake, N.J., who
will fly to an Atlantic Fleet aircraft carrier to observe
operations. He teaches U.S. history to eighth-graders at South
Plainfield Middle School in South Plainfield, N.J. He said he
aspires to teach history at the U.S. Naval Academy in Annapolis,
Md.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Navy was my career goal since I was a freshman in high
school,'' he wrote. ''Bad knees kept me from achieving that goal.''
</P>
<P>
   For the Coast Guard, it will be Stephanie Kelley, 22, who
recently graduated from Duke University in Durham, N.C., with a
biology degree. She will travel to Houston and Galveston, Texas, to
experience several facets of search and rescue operations,
including training as a rescue swimmer.
</P>
<P>
   ''This opportunity to be a part of the search and rescue team
for a day could be the clinching moment -- whether I shed my
civilian clothing to try for a position within the U.S. Coast
Guard,'' she wrote.
</P>
<P>
   That is exactly what the Coast Guard and the other services hope
the ''fantasy careers'' exercise will accomplish: Spread the word
of the careers available in the military.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   Pentagon news release:
http://www.defenselink.mil/news/Aug2000/b08082000--bt490-00.html
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
