<HEADLINE> Georgia Seeks Red Cross Workers  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   TBILISI, Georgia (AP) -- Georgian authorities are negotiating for
the release of three Red Cross workers kidnapped near the Chechen
border, the Interior Ministry said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The workers disappeared last week and had been feared kidnapped
by Chechen gunmen. The ministry said that the three were kidnapped
and that talks have begun on securing their release.
</P>
<P>
   The ministry would not say who the captors are or give any other
details.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Cross in Georgia said earlier Tuesday that it had
suspended its work with refugees in Georgia near the Chechen border
after the disappearance. The refugees fled fighting between
separatist rebels and Russian troops in Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   ''We still have no contact with our colleagues,'' Red Cross
spokeswoman Pauline Serneux said in the Georgian capital Tbilisi.
</P>
<P>
   The missing team was last seen Friday while on the way to the
Pankisi Gorge, a border district where thousands of Chechen
refugees are staying, the Red Cross headquarters in Geneva said in
a statement.
</P>
<P>
   The Georgian Prosecutor General's Office said Tuesday they have
information the aid workers were abducted and that they are alive,
but declined to release any details.
</P>
<P>
   The missing workers were from France, Italy and Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   International aid groups pulled out of Chechnya and surrounding
regions after a wave of kidnappings and killings of Russians and
foreigners that followed the 1994-96 Chechnya war.
</P>
<P>
   Six Red Cross workers were shot to death in 1996 as they slept
in a hospital compound in Noviye Atagi in Chechnya and at least
three foreign aid workers were kidnapped in the republic in recent
years.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
