<HEADLINE> Giordano attacks Lieberman's ''Extreme Liberal'' record  </HEADLINE>
By MATTHEW DALY
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) - U.S. Sen. Joseph Lieberman, the new
Democratic nominee for vice president, has won praise nationally as
a moderate willing to reach across party lines.
</P>
<P>
   But back in Connecticut, his Republican Senate opponent attacked
Lieberman as a ''chameleon'' whose conservative talk masks a
liberal voting record.
</P>
<P>
   Waterbury Mayor Philip Giordano, who is challenging Lieberman
for a U.S. Senate seat, denounced the two-term senator as ''a very
extreme liberal'' whose views do not represent the state.
</P>
<P>
   ''When it really counts, Lieberman sticks with his party,''
Giordano said, attacking Lieberman's record on Social Security,
crime, taxes and a host of other issues.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference Tuesday - just minutes before Lieberman
officially joined the Democratic ticket in Nashville - Giordano
criticized Lieberman's voting record over his 12-year Senate
career.
</P>
<P>
   Giordano handed out a 40-page report titled ''The Worst of
Senator Joseph Lieberman,'' in which he slammed Lieberman for votes
he said failed to protect seniors, funded pornography and even left
children open to attack by pedophiles. Giordano denied he was
making personal attacks and said he was merely exposing Lieberman's
true record.
</P>
<P>
   ''Records are a matter of target, if you will,'' Giordano said,
adding that his own service as Waterbury mayor and state
representative is also open to scrutiny.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman spokesman Dan Gerstein would not address Giordano's
claims.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is a really special day and proud day for Sen. Lieberman.
He doesn't want to spoil it by getting dragged down into some petty
politics,'' said Gerstein.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic state Chairman Edward L. Marcus ridiculed Giordano's
attack as the act of a ''desperate'' man, noting that Giordano
trailed Lieberman by 57 percentage points in a recent poll.
</P>
<P>
   ''With this kind of campaign it's no wonder the city of
Waterbury is in the shape that it's in,'' Marcus said.
</P>
<P>
   One of the more sensational charges made by Giordano involved a
1990 vote he said showed Lieberman was ''opposed to protecting
children from pedophiles.'' The bill involved organizations in
Washington, D.C., that were seeking to bar ''any person convicted
of or charged with a sexual offense involving a minor from coaching
or teaching,'' Giordano's memo said. But when asked what
organizations, specifically, were targeted in the legislation,
Giordano said he did not know.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he was accusing Lieberman of supporting pedophiles,
Giordano said no, but added, ''He certainly had an opportunity to
protect children from pedophiles and he didn't do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Giordano also attacked Lieberman for supporting funding for the
National Endowment for the Arts, even though the agency has
sponsored works that some consider obscene or pornographic, and
criticized Lieberman for voting to increase the federal gas tax and
opposing bills to eliminate the so-called marriage penalty,
eliminate estate taxes for the wealthy and outlaw flag burning.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
