<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kashmiri Militants End Cease-Fire  </HEADLINE>
By AMIR ZIA
<TEXT>
<P>
   ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) -- A Kashmiri militant group called off
its cease-fire with India on Tuesday, saying New Delhi had
squandered a chance for peace in the long and bloody Kashmir
dispute by refusing to let Pakistan join negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   India, however, blamed Pakistan for the setback, accusing it of
pressuring the militant group Hezb-ul Mujahedeen to resume attacks
in the Indian-held part of the Himalayan territory, long a
flashpoint between the two nations.
</P>
<P>
   Though other militant groups had not joined it, the cease-fire
called July 24 by Hezb-ul Mujahedeen had been seen as a ray of hope
for an end to the conflict in Kashmir, where Muslim guerrillas have
been leading a separatist insurgency since 1989.
</P>
<P>
   ''This peace offensive has not been reciprocated by India, who
have demonstrated their traditional intransigence,'' Hezb-ul
Mujahedeen chief Sayed Salahuddin told journalists in the Pakistani
capital, Islamabad.
</P>
<P>
   India, however, insisted it was still committed to the peace
process.
</P>
<P>
   ''Pakistani agencies have put intense pressure on the Hezb-ul
Mujahedeen in Pakistan-occupied Kashmir to sabotage the
cease-fire,'' the Indian government said in a statement Tuesday
after Prime Minister Atal Bihari Vajpayee met with his top Cabinet
ministers.
</P>
<P>
   India had halted operations against Hezb-ul Mujahedeen in
response to the cease-fire, though it continued battling with other
militant groups.
</P>
<P>
   Independent Star News television said Indian troops in Kashmir
had gone on high alert after Tuesday's announcement amid concerns
of a resurgence in fighting.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if operations would resume against the Hezb-ul Mujahedeen,
Indian Defense Ministry spokesman P.S. Bhatnagar said only, ''The
Indian army has to take all precautions and steps to maintain
security and safety of the people.''
</P>
<P>
   Kashmir, divided between India and Pakistan in 1947, is one of
the most volatile regions in the world and the source of
international concern that an escalation of violence could lead to
a larger conflict between India and Pakistan, the world's two
newest nuclear powers.
</P>
<P>
   India refused Hezb-ul Mujahedeen's demands to include Pakistan
in peace talks. New Delhi has long refused direct talks on Kashmir
with Islamabad, which it accuses of supporting Muslim militant
groups in the territory.
</P>
<P>
   Pakistan, which says its support for militants is limited to
political and moral help, insists the 53-year Kashmir dispute
cannot be solved without its involvement.
</P>
<P>
   The Indian government accused Pakistan on Tuesday of encouraging
other militant groups to step up attacks during the cease-fire --
including a string of attacks last week in which militants killed
102 people in two days.
</P>
<P>
   Salahuddin said Hezb-ul Mujahedeen had risked its reputation
with its cease-fire offer. Other guerrilla groups suspended Hezb-ul
Mujahedeen from their umbrella organization, the United Jehad
Council, because of the cease-fire.
</P>
<P>
   ''It needs to be pointed out that we put our entire credibility
of 12 years at stake for our (desire) to facilitate a peaceful
resolution,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Kashmir has been the flashpoint for two wars between India and
Pakistan since the end of British rule in the subcontinent. Both
countries claim Kashmir in its entirety.
</P>
<P>
   Pakistan has been pressing for a vote by Kashmiris on both the
Indian and Pakistani sides to decide whether a united Kashmir would
join Islamic Pakistan or Hindu India.
</P>
<P>
   New Delhi opposes the vote, which is in keeping with a 1948
United Nations resolution.
</P>
<P>
   Other militant groups welcomed the end to the cease-fire.
</P>
<P>
   ''There is no solution but jihad (holy war),'' said a statement
from Al Badr, a sizable fighting group. ''India is our enemy.''
Like Al Badr, the group Lashkar-e-Tayyab said fighting would
continue.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
