<BODY>
<HEADLINE> FDA OKs Corticosteroid Inhalant  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- An inhalant drug that can be used by asthmatic
children as young as 1 year was approved Tuesday by the Food and
Drug Administration.
</P>
<P>
   The drug, sold under the brand name Pulmicort Respules, is a
corticosteroid formulated for use in a nebulizer, a type of fogging
machine. The drug will be the first corticosteroid approved for the
very young.
</P>
<P>
   ''Until now, we haven't had a formulation of corticosteroids for
use by children this young,'' said Dr. John Jenkins of the Food and
Drug Administration. The drug can be used by asthmatics between the
ages of 1 and 8, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Jenkins said inhalant applicators that delivered corticosteroids
as a dry powder previously were approved for children no younger
than 4. That application ''required the cooperation'' of the
patient and was not appropriate for the very young, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The new formulation of the drug, Jenkins said, allows it to be
administered with a nebulizer, which creates a fog-like aerosol
spray containing the drug.
</P>
<P>
   Young children are given the drug through a breathing mask, he
said. A bit of the drug is inhaled with each breath inside the
mask.
</P>
<P>
   Jenkins said the new approval is important because
corticosteroids are the basic maintenance drug for asthma patients.
The drug reduces bronchial inflammation that often precedes an
asthma attack. It is designed for use once or twice daily as an
attack preventive. Acute asthma attacks are treated with a
faster-acting brochodilator drug.
</P>
<P>
   Approval of the new formulation of Pulmicort Respules follows
three 12-week studies involving 1,000 patients between the ages of
6 months and 8 years. All the patients had persistent asthma.
</P>
<P>
   Side effects from the drug included respiratory infection,
congestion and coughing. Patients using the drug should avoid
exposure to chicken pox and measles. Children on the drug who have
not been vaccinated and who become exposed to chicken pox should
see a doctor without delay, the FDA said.
</P>
<P>
   Pulmicort Respules is manufactured by the AstraZeneca Group of
Wayne, Pa.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   For more information on asthma:
http://www.nlm.nih.gov/hmd/breath/breathhome.html
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
