<HEADLINE> Farmers in 35 rain-soaked counties now eligible for low-interest loans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) - U.S. Agriculture Secretary Dan Glickman
Tuesday declared 35 of the state's counties agricultural disaster
areas due to excessive rain, flooding, high winds and hail.
</P>
<P>
   The declaration, which had been sought by Gov. George Pataki,
makes farmers in those counties eligible for emergency low-interest
loans from the federal Farm Service Agency. Farmers have eight
months to apply for the loans.
</P>
<P>
   Economic losses for apple growers in the mid-Hudson region alone
are already estimated at $10 million.
</P>
<P>
   Farmers further upstate likewise stand to lose millions of
dollars due to damaged fields and orchards.
</P>
<P>
   The counties of Columbia, Dutchess, Greene, Monroe, Oneida,
Orange, Saratoga, Schenectady, Schoharie, Ulster, and Yates were
labeled primary disaster areas. Eligible contiguous counties are:
Albany, Delaware, Fulton, Genesee, Hamilton, Herkimer, Lewis,
Livingston, Madison, Montgomery, Ontario, Otsego, Orleans, Oswego,
Putnam, Rensselaer, Rockland, Saratoga, Schuyler, Seneca, Steuben,
Warren, Washington, and Wayne
</P>
</TEXT>
