<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jerusalem Leaders Talk of Election  </HEADLINE>
By LAURIE COPANS
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM (AP) -- The leader of the opposition party and a former
ally of Prime Minister Ehud Barak met Tuesday in a flurry of
political activity in preparation for possible early elections.
</P>
<P>
   As part of discussions on a possible alliance prior to
elections, Likud party leader Ariel Sharon met with David Levy, who
resigned as foreign minister last week to protest concessions he
said Barak was making to the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   The meeting came a week after Barak lost several votes in the
parliament including a preliminary vote on a bill for early
elections. Three parties bolted Barak's coalition last month
complaining he was offering Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat too
much at the Camp David summit.
</P>
<P>
   Both supporters and opponents of Barak say they expect elections
in the coming months.
</P>
<P>
   Eli Ishai, a leader of the Shas religious party, which also
withdrew from Barak's coalition, met Tuesday with Benjamin
Netanyahu, who lost the prime minister race to Barak in 1999
elections, Israel Television reported.
</P>
<P>
   The parliament recessed last week for three months, putting off
further votes on the election bill unless a special session is
called. Barak hopes to conclude a peace agreement with the
Palestinians in the meantime.
</P>
<P>
   A poll in the Yediot Ahronot daily last week showed Netanyahu
ahead of Barak by 46 percent to 42 percent if he chooses to run in
elections.
</P>
<P>
   Netanyahu dropped out of politics after the May 1999 election
but has made public appearances recently, and there is growing
speculation he will return to politics. The polls show him faring
better than Sharon, his successor as leader of the hardline Likud
party, in a contest against Barak.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
