<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-08 20:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rwanda Tries to Save Congo Deal  </HEADLINE>
By HRVOJE HRANJSKI
<TEXT>
<P>
   KIGALI, Rwanda (AP) -- In a bid to prevent the return of war in
Congo, Rwanda told a U.N. envoy Tuesday it would unilaterally
withdraw from front-line positions and hand them over to U.N.
observers.
</P>
<P>
   The Rwandan initiative would create a 125-mile wide corridor
from Dekese in western Congo to Moba on the eastern shores of Lake
Tanganyika, where Rwandan troops and the allied Congolese rebels
have clashed with President Laurent Kabila's army despite a
year-old cease-fire.
</P>
<P>
   ''Rwanda doesn't believe in a military solution for Congo,''
said Rwandan presidential adviser Patrick Mazimhaka, who had made
the formal offer.
</P>
<P>
   ''The answer to a question whether we will go to war is no. We
shall try to convince the government in Kinshasa that a solution
lies in negotiated settlement.''
</P>
<P>
   Kemal Morjane, a U.N. envoy for Congo, welcomed the Rwandan
initiative but warned, ''this is something which we need to discuss
further for details'' with Kabila's government.
</P>
<P>
   Rwandan-backed Congo rebels also told Morjane they would pull
back immediately, 6 miles from the front lines at first, then
farther as U.N. forces move in.
</P>
<P>
   The peace accord to disengage warring troops in Congo and make
room for a U.N. force that would oversee their withdrawal from the
country was agreed upon in April by Kabila, the rebels and five
foreign countries backing one side or another.
</P>
<P>
   But the Congolese government has since blocked its
implementation, and rejected an African-appointed mediator for
talks on Congo's postwar government.
</P>
<P>
   Morjane said the United Nations had four battalions from
Pakistan, Senegal and Morocco ready for deployment in Congo, but
that a cease-fire, security for U.N. personnel and their freedom of
movement were still lacking.
</P>
<P>
   Southern African leaders meeting in Windhoek, Namibia, on Monday
called for a summit Aug. 14 on Congo in Lusaka, Zambia. Although
invited to the meeting of the Southern African Development
Community, Kabila failed to show up.
</P>
<P>
   Rwandan army chief of staff, Brig. Gen. Kayumba Nyamwasa said
the Congolese government and their Zimbabwean allies had repeatedly
violated the cease-fire in southern Congo.
</P>
<P>
   Rwandan military officials said they had killed at least 12
government or Zimbabwean soldiers when they tried to break through
Rwanda's defense, on one occasion using a helicopter gunship.
</P>
<P>
   Fighting has also been reported in northern Congo, where a
Ugandan-backed rebel group fought battles with government soldiers,
a rebel spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   Rwanda and Uganda accuse Kabila of arming the Hutu militiamen
who set up bases in eastern Congo after taking part in the 1994
genocide of more than 500,000 people in Rwanda. But they have
disagreed over which of the three rebel factions to support.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-08-00 2033 </TRAILER>
