<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-08 20:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Signs Hunt House Law  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton on Tuesday signed bipartisan
legislation to add the home of Jane Hunt, a pioneer of the women's
rights movement to a historical park in New York, where first lady
Hillary Rodham Clinton is running for a Senate seat.
</P>
<P>
   Under the legislation, the National Trust for Historic
Preservation will buy the home and donate it to the National Parks
Service to expand the Women's Rights National Historical Park in
Waterloo, N.Y., and Seneca Falls, N.Y. In 1848, early advocates of
women's rights met at the home and resolved to convene the nation's
first women's rights convention.
</P>
<P>
   ''A century and a half later, the addition of the Hunt House to
the historical park is a fitting tribute to all those who have
engaged in the struggle for women's rights,'' Clinton said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
