<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-08 20:41 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tuesday's Canada News Briefs  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated PressNote: All dollars are Canadian unless otherwise noted
Blasts at Northern Manitoba Smelter Injure 12 Workers
<TEXT>
<P>
   FLIN FLON, Manitoba (AP) -- A series of blasts that injured a
dozen workers at a smelter early Tuesday must be thoroughly
investigated to see if company safety practices were at fault, says
a union official.
</P>
<P>
   ''We will not speculate on the cause until the investigation is
complete,'' Bill Bage, president of the United Steelworkers' Local
7106, said of the accident at the Hudson Bay Mining and Smelting
facility located on the Manitoba-Saskatchewan boundary.
</P>
<P>
   But Bage added the union is concerned about safety at the
worksite.
</P>
<P>
   The blasts occurred about 1:30 a.m. as a furnace was being
cooled down during regular maintenance.
</P>
<P>
   Four of the injured workers were flown to hospitals in Winnipeg,
Regina and Edmonton.
</P>
<P>
   At least three of those workers were in critical condition. No
one was killed.
</P>
<P>
   The smelter and the copper-zinc mine, found 675 kilometers
northwest of Winnipeg, are the major employers in the area, with
1,400 people on the payroll.
Mudslide Forces Evacuation in Trois-Rivieres, Quebec
</P>
<P>
   TROIS-RIVIERES, Quebec (AP) -- About 30 people were forced out of
their homes Tuesday after heavy rain triggered a mudslide.
</P>
<P>
   No one was injured in the incident, but several homes were
damaged as basements filled with thick mud and water.
</P>
<P>
   Marie-Lou Martel was sitting in her living room when the slide
occurred.
</P>
<P>
   ''It sounded like something collapsed,'' Martel told
Radio-Canada's all-news channel, RDI.
</P>
<P>
   ''Then my window broke and I was covered with mud. When we tried
to get out it was hard to open the door.''
</P>
<P>
   The storm began mid-afternoon in this city located halfway
between Montreal and Quebec City.
</P>
<P>
   The drainage system quickly became flooded, leaving drivers to
maneuver through water that covered their vehicles' tires.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the evacuees were expected to return to their homes
later Tuesday. However, at least two or three families were to be
displaced longer because of mud in their basements.
E. Coli Vaccine Moves To Final Testing Stage
</P>
<P>
   OTTAWA (AP) -- Federal scientists have teamed up with a venture
capital company to test a potential vaccine against deadly E. coli
bacteria.
</P>
<P>
   If successful, the vaccine could eradicate the E. coli 0157
strain that contributed to the deaths of six people and left
hundreds ill recently in Walkerton, Ontario.
</P>
<P>
   The National Research Council has signed an agreement with
Foragen Technology Ventures Inc. of Guelph, Ontario, to pay for
testing of the vaccine on cattle.
</P>
<P>
   Cattle feces are considered the primary source of E. coli, which
has been found in community well water.
</P>
<P>
   Tests of the vaccine on lab mice have proven effective in
killing the bacteria.
</P>
<P>
   Tests on cattle are being conducted this month at the Veterinary
Infectious Disease Organization in Saskatoon.
</P>
<P>
   Results of the clinical trials are expected within two months.
</P>
<P>
   The vaccine works by attaching a harmless bacteria to the E.
coli 0157, creating antibodies to kill the deadly strain.
</P>
<P>
   ------
Lt.-Gen. Mike Jeffery Is New Canadian Army Commander
</P>
<P>
   OTTAWA (AP) -- Lt.-Gen. Mike Jeffery formally assumed command of
the Canadian army Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Jeffery, who had been working on reorganizing the reserves,
replaced Lt.-Gen. Bill Leach, who will officially retire from the
Forces next month after 40 years of service.
</P>
<P>
   Jeffery is a career artilleryman who rose from apprentice
soldier in 1964, to the ranks of the generals.
</P>
<P>
   He is a former commandant of the Canadian Land Forces Command
and Staff College. He commanded the military's Y2K program last
year.
</P>
<P>
   He had little to say about his plans as he took command.
</P>
<P>
   ''I have only just assumed the reins of command and I really do
have to get a very good sense of where the army is.''
</P>
<P>
   Leach presided during tumultuous times, as deputy commander and
then commander of the army, when the military was struggling with
the Somalia affair, a wide range of reforms and shrinking budgets
and personnel.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
