<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-08 20:43 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Republican Ad Denounces Gore  </HEADLINE>
By H. JOSEF HEBERT
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- A new Republican ad criticizes Vice President
Al Gore for getting thousands of dollars in royalty payments from a
zinc mining operation on Gore land in Tennessee, alleging the
company has been found polluting a nearby river.
</P>
<P>
   The ad by the Republican National Committee accuses Gore of
hypocrisy for attacking Gov. George W. Bush's environmental record
in Texas, while he ''has allowed mining companies to mine zinc from
his property'' and pollute drinking water.
</P>
<P>
   The ad, part of $3.7 million campaign focusing on environment,
began being aired Tuesday in 17 battleground states from Florida to
New Mexico and Wisconsin.
</P>
<P>
   The Gore campaign immediately denounced the ad as being loose
with the facts.
</P>
<P>
   The vice president ''has always insisted that the companies that
operate the mine on his property do so in a way that doesn't harm
the environment,'' said Ron Klain, a senior Gore campaign adviser.
''Where minor problems have arisen they were resolved quickly and
in cooperation with state environmental officials and the operator
of the mine.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore over the years has acknowledged royalty payments of $20,000
a year from a succession of mining companies that hold leases on
the Gore property near Carthage, Tenn. He has reported the payments
in annual income statements.
</P>
<P>
   The zinc-bearing property located across the Caney Fork river
from Gore's farm was purchased by Albert Gore Sr., in 1973 from
Occidental Minerals, a subsidiary of Occidental Petroleum, with
which the senior Gore had had a close relationship. The senior Gore
sold it to his son a year later, passing along the annual royalty
right
</P>
<P>
   According to a recent article in The Wall Street Journal, the
mining companies -- Pasminco Ltd., and a predecessor, Savage Zinc
Inc. -- have been cited four times since 1997 for violating state
water quality standards.
</P>
<P>
   Last May, zinc levels in the Caney Fork near the mine exceeded
the maximum allowed by state and federal water quality standards.
In January, a pipe failure caused too much waste water to escape
into the river.
</P>
<P>
   State officials have acknowledged these problems were quickly
resolved and that overall the mining company has a good
environmental record, said Klain.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's hypocrisy going on here,'' said GOP spokesman Bill
Pascoe, who noted recent attacks by Gore on Bush's environmental
record in Texas. ''This is his own property and it's being cited by
the Tennessee Department of Environment and Conservation.''
</P>
<P>
   The GOP ad also reiterates claims often made by the Bush
campaign that Texas has dramatically reduced the amount of toxic
releases from industrial plants since Bush became governor in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ''George Bush is cleaning up Texas,'' assures a narator in the
ad. ''...Texas leads America in reducing toxic pollution.''
</P>
<P>
   That claim, however, has been the subject of intense dispute.
</P>
<P>
   The ad cites statistics from the federal Environmental
Protection Agency that shows total toxic chemical releases from
Texas industry declined by 43 million pounds between 1995 and 1998,
more than any other state.
</P>
<P>
   Daniel Weiss of the Sierra Club calls that figure misleading.
All but about 5 million of those pounds occurred in between 1995
and 1996, early in Bush's tenure, while emissions actually
increased slightly in 1998. Toxic release into water and onto land
increases over the four-year period.
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, argues Weiss, the large volume reductions reflect
the huge amounts of toxic chemicals -- 263 million pounds in 1998 --
being released by the state's petrochemical plants and other
industrial sources.
</P>
<P>
   On a percentage basis, Texas has cut toxic industrial pollution
by 14 percent, according to the EPA statistics, with 23 other
states having done better. Still, Texas' record is far better than
the national average of 5.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Dan Bartlett, a Bush campaign spokesman, said the volume figure
is a fair gauge of environmental improvement because it's that much
less pollution being put into the environment. He said the state's
large overall release numbers reflect its high concentration of
petrochemical plants.
</P>
<P>
   Replies Klain: ''The fact is that Texas has led the country in
industrial pollution. Every year since 1995, Texas has been the
most polluted state in the nation, leading in combined releases
into the air, water and soil.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
