<HEADLINE> First lady to appear on 'Tonight Show'  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   LOS ANGELES (AP) - Hillary Rodham Clinton, who appeared on David
Letterman's ''Late Show'' in January, is giving Jay Leno equal
time.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Senate candidate in New York, will join Leno on ''The
Tonight Show'' Friday, just days before the Aug. 14 start of the
Democratic convention in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Leno hasn't shied away from poking fun at the first lady, who is
making her first appearance on his NBC program.
</P>
<P>
   ''Do you get the feeling that every time (John) McCain called
(George W.) Bush 'friend,' he felt the same way as Hillary every
time she calls Bill 'my husband,''' Leno joked last week.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton appeared on CBS' ''Late Show'' after weeks of needling
from Letterman, who called her a carpetbagger who was afraid to
join him. When she did, however, the first lady received kid-glove
treatment.
</P>
<P>
   Leno will play host during the convention week to a potential
first lady: Tipper Gore, whose husband, Vice President Al Gore,
will be nominated as the Democratic presidential candidate next
week.
</P>
