<HEADLINE> Lions' Batch's Knee Looks OK  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNIVERSITY CENTER, Mich. (AP) -- Detroit Lions quarterback
Charlie Batch underwent a successful medical examination, coach
Bobby Ross said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Batch, who broke a bone in his knee in early June, spent the
past two days in Birmingham, Ala., having his injured right leg
examined.
</P>
<P>
   ''Everything looked very good medically,'' Ross said. ''The knee
looked good. The calcium buildup was there, and now we have to see
how he reacts to the running phase.''
</P>
<P>
   With Batch still out, the Lions' other quarterbacks had a
productive practice Tuesday. Stoney Case threw three long touch
passes, and Steve Stenstrom and Cory Sauter also threw effectively.
</P>
<P>
   ''I thought we made progress offensively in our throwing game,''
Ross said. ''I think we started throwing the ball a little bit
better, timing looked a little bit better and our rhythm on offense
in and out of the huddle was good.''
</P>
</TEXT>
