<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-08 20:55 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia Rids Reporter's Travel Rules  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW (AP) -- Russian prosecutors have lifted travel
restrictions on a journalist for U.S.-funded Radio Liberty detained
in Chechnya earlier this year, news reports said.
</P>
<P>
   Andrei Babitsky, who had angered the Russian military by
covering the war in Chechnya from the rebels' side, could not
travel to Romania to receive a prize last month for his Chechnya
reporting because of the travel ban.
</P>
<P>
   The restrictions were lifted at the request of ''prominent
public figures,'' the ITAR-Tass news agency quoted Interior
Ministry spokesman Vladimir Martynov as saying.
</P>
<P>
   Babitsky's lawyer Genri Reznik said the request came from
parliament members Yuri Shchekochikin and Sergei Yushenkov and the
chief editor of the Novaya Gazeta investigative weekly, Dmitry
Muratov, the Interfax news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
   Babitsky's arrest in January helped draw international attention
to Russia's treatment of civilian prisoners in Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   He was detained for not having proper accreditation then held
for two weeks in a detention center in Chechnya, where he said he
saw innocent men tortured by Russian police. He then disappeared
for weeks, causing coworkers to say they feared the military had
killed him.
</P>
<P>
   He resurfaced in Russian custody and was eventually released on
condition that he not leave Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   Russia's Interior Ministry filed charges last month against
Babitsky for knowingly using false documents. If found guilty,
Babitsky faces up to two years in a labor camp.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-08-00 2055 </TRAILER>
