<DOCTYPE> SUBDIVIDED </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-08 21:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 9 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Tuesday, Aug. 8, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Source: Firestone To Recall Tires
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   DETROIT (AP) -- Bridgestone/Firestone Inc. plans to announce tomorrow a
recall of about 20 million of its tires for light trucks and sport utility
vehicles that have been implicated in more than 40 fatal accidents, a source
familiar with the decision said. Most of the Firestone ATX, ATX II and
Wilderness tires are on Ford Explorers, the top-selling SUV, but the recall will
include tires on all brands of vehicles, the source said. The recalled tires
will be replaced by other Firestone tires, the source said.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Buchanans Claim Reform Victory
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   LONG BEACH, Calif. (AP) -- Two days before its nominating convention, the
Reform Party split loudly today as supporters of founder Ross Perot walked out
of a closed meeting, leaving backers of Pat Buchanan inside and the party's
future in question. ''We have won,'' claimed Buchanan's sister and campaign
manager, Bay. ''It's Pat Buchanan's nomination.'' But foes were seeking to block
the conservative commentator from the party's $12.5 million in federal campaign
funds if he wins the nomination.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Gore-Lieberman Campaign Starts
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) -- Democratic presidential campaigner Al Gore today
introduced running mate Joseph Lieberman at a rally. Sen. Lieberman of
Connecticut credited Gore with barrier-busting ''chutzpah'' and said they would
work to ''renew the moral center of this nation.'' With a Jew on a major party's
national ticket for the first time, Gore said, ''We will tear down an old wall
of division.''
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Clinton Tours Wildfire Damage
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   BURGDORF, Idaho (AP) -- President Clinton today took an aerial tour of Idaho
forest lands charred by one of 66 fires that have burned more than 866,312 acres
across 11 Western states. He thanked some of the nearly 1,300 civilian and
military firefighters who have been working to control the blazes. Clinton was
joined by Forest Service chief Mike Dombeck. The president said he will release
$150 million in emergency funds to the Agriculture Department for firefighting
efforts.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Bomb Kills 7 in Moscow
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   MOSCOW (AP) -- A bomb tore through a crowded underground walkway in central
Moscow on Tuesday, killing at least seven people and sending dozens of wounded
pedestrians staggering out. Suspicion for the bombing immediately fell on
Chechen rebels, and there were fears of a renewed terrorist onslaught in the
Russian capital. President Vladimir Putin ordered police on alert around the
country.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Chile Court Ends Pinochet Immunity
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) -- Chile's Supreme Court Tuesday lifted Gen. Augusto
Pinochet's immunity from prosecution, paving the way for the former dictator to
be tried on human rights charges. But chances for a quick trial appeared slim.
Pinochet's supporters in Congress announced a bill to try to block a trial of
the 84-year-old Pinochet on grounds of health.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Teen Birth Rate Lowest in 60 Years
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   ATLANTA (AP) -- Births to teen-agers have fallen to their lowest rate in the
60 years that statistics have been kept, a government agency said today. Births
to girls ages 15 to 19 dropped last year to 49.6 per 1,000, down 3 percent from
1998 and 20 percent from 1991, according to the National Center for Health
Statistics. It was the eighth consecutive year of decline, the NCHS said.
Analysts said more teens than ever understand the importance of safe sex and
more teens are abstaining from sex.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Productivity Growth Best in 17 Years
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Americans' productivity surged ahead over the past 12
months at the fastest pace in 17 years while labor costs declined, the first
time they have dropped since 1984, the Labor Department reported today. Both
numbers were much better than expected. Economists said it now seemed highly
unlikely that the Federal Reserve will boost interest rates for a seventh time
when the central bank meets again Aug. 22.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Dow Ends Up 110; Nasdaq Falls 14
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Blue chip stocks closed higher today amid optimism that
interest rates will hold steady, but technology issues fell on profit taking.
The Dow Jones industrial average ended up 109.88 at 10,976.89. On the NYSE,
gainers led losers by a 5-to-4 margin. The Nasdaq composite index was down 14.44
at 3,848.55.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Reports: Braves, Jones Reach Deal
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Atlanta Braves third baseman Chipper Jones, last year's NL
MVP, has agreed to a $90 million, six-year deal to remain with the Braves,
Newsday and ESPN.com reported today. Jones, 28, would be eligible for free
agency after the season. The $15 million per year average would equal the
richest deal in baseball. He is batting .307 this season with 24 home runs and
79 RBIs.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
AP NewsBrief by HOWARD SINER
</SUBHEAD>
</TEXT>
