<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Judge gives final approval to Synthroid settlement  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   CHICAGO (AP) - A federal judge has given final approval to a
settlement calling for hundreds of thousands of users of the
thyroid drug Synthroid and insurance companies to share up to $137
million to settle allegations that the drug's maker suppressed
unfavorable research.
</P>
<P>
   Under terms of the agreement - granted final approval Aug. 4 by
U.S. District Judge Elaine Bucklo - Mount Olive, N.J.-based Knoll
Pharmaceutical Co. will pay about $91 million to 778,000 consumers,
less attorneys' fees and costs. Consumers will each receive about
$111 if they began taking Synthroid before Jan. 1, 1995, and about
$74 each if they began taking it after that date. The company
agreed to pay another $46 million to insurance companies.
</P>
<P>
   The settlement agreement was reached in October 1997, following
publication earlier that year of a study that concluded Synthroid,
which dominates the $600 million market for thyroid drugs, was no
better than three cheaper alternatives. The other drugs are two to
three times less expensive than Synthroid.
</P>
<P>
   Knoll, which hired pharmacist Betty Dong from the University of
California at San Francisco to conduct the study in 1990, strongly
disagreed with its results and kept it from being published, Dong
told the Journal of the American Medical Association.
</P>
<P>
   Knoll admitted no wrongdoing under the settlement, but said it
agreed to the settlement to avoid a prolonged legal battle. The
quality of the drug and the safety of the drug were never
questioned in any of the cases.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Knoll agreed to pay 37 states a total of $41.8
million to settle the same charges made by individual Synthroid
users. Knoll did not admit any wrongdoing in that settlement,
either.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
