<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More mosquitoes in city, Suffolk, Rockland test positive  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) - Thirteen more pools of mosquitoes were found
infected with the West Nile virus, including five on Staten Island,
the state Health Department said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Mosquitoes from Rockland County and Suffolk County also tested
positive, the department said.
</P>
<P>
   There were no new human cases announced. Only one person, a man
from Staten Island who is recovering, has been reported infected so
far this year.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, seven people in the metropolitan area were killed as
the virus, which is transmitted from mosquitoes to humans, made its
first known appearance in the Western Hemisphere. Various testing
and mosquito-control measures have been taken since, including
regular collections of mosquitoes in traps to see where the
infection is present.
</P>
<P>
   The Health Department said four collections, or pools, were
found positive in Rockland, where two positive pools had been found
before; four infected pools were found in Suffolk, for a total of
35 there; and five were found in Staten Island, bringing the New
York City total to eight - seven in Staten Island and one in
Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   Previously, Westchester and Orange counties had positive
mosquitoes.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this season, the discovery of infected mosquitoes
prompted ground spraying of pesticides. But most of the mosquito
infections announced Tuesday were in areas that have been sprayed
since the mosquitoes were collected.
</P>
<P>
   Rockland County Health Commissioner Gabriel Guardarramas said
there was no need for further spraying in Rockland.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-08-08-00 2154 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000808.0183 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-08 21:54 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Korean Workers Shop With Credit  </HEADLINE>
By SANG-HUN CHOE
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEOUL, South Korea (AP) -- For the first time, communist North
Korea is allowing South Korean workers there to flash the ultimate
capitalist symbol: the credit card.
</P>
<P>
   But the isolated North is far from embracing the free market
ways of the South. The workers can only use South Korean cards in a
fenced enclave in a rural village on the North's northeastern
coast, and no North Korean entity is involved in the deal.
</P>
<P>
   The South Koreans, whose movements are tightly restricted, are
among 800 workers building Western-designed nuclear reactors near
Shinpo under a 1994 deal between North Korea and the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Their enclosure has a supermarket, a karaoke bar, a barber shop,
a billiard hall and other amenities operated by South Korea's
Daewoo conglomerate, which has hired North Korean attendants.
</P>
<P>
   The attendants and workers, who are required by North Korea to
pay in U.S. dollars, often run out of change. So Seoul's Korea
Exchange Bank began issuing credit cards two weeks ago, said Lee
Kil-sung, an official of Seoul's Financial Supervisory Service.
</P>
<P>
   So far, 42 South Koreans have taken out credit cards.
</P>
<P>
   A U.S.-led consortium, called the Korean Peninsula Energy
Development Organization, is building two reactors in return for a
freeze on the North's nuclear program. U.S. and South Korean
officials had believed North Korea was using its Soviet-designed
reactors for a nuclear weapons program.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-08-00 2154 </TRAILER>
