<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Duke Golfer Beth Bauer To Turn Pro  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   DURHAM, N.C. (AP) -- Duke golfer Beth Bauer has decided not to
return for her junior year and will turn pro instead.
</P>
<P>
   Bauer, who hinted last month at the ShopRite LPGA Classic that
she might turn pro, will make her professional debut next month at
the State Farm Rail Classic, Golfweek magazine reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ''In college golf I don't feel like I can develop my game
fully,'' she told Golfweek. ''I'm such an individual. I like to do
things on my own, and with the team, I couldn't always do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Bauer, 20, is among the nation's top-ranked women amateurs.
</P>
<P>
   She was a two-time, first-team All-America and won three college
titles, including the 1999 ACC championship and NCAA East regional.
She was also a member of Duke's 1999 NCAA national championship
team.
</P>
<P>
   ''She has a dream as strong as anybody I've ever known,'' Duke
coach Dan Brooks said. ''I don't think she had anybody telling her
what to do, so I admire her for following her dream.''
</P>
<P>
   Bauer played this summer on her second victorious Curtis Cup
team and has played in four LPGA events this year.
</P>
<P>
   She tied for 35th in the Nabisco Championship and tied for 38th
in the Jamie Farr Kroger Classic but missed the cut in the LPGA
ShopRite Classic and the U.S. Women's Open.
</P>
<P>
   ''This summer, I didn't play as well as I hoped,'' said Bauer,
who is playing this week in the U.S. Women's Amateur at Waverly
Country Club in Portland, Ore. ''But I'm learning, and it's been a
good experience.''
</P>
</TEXT>
