<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-08 22:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rangers 11, Indians 2  </HEADLINE>
By TOM WITHERS
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND (AP) -- Kenny Rogers cooled down Cleveland by pitching
eight strong innings Tuesday night and Gabe Kapler extended his
hitting streak to 22 games as the Texas Rangers snapped the
Indians' six-game winning streak with a 11-2 victory.
</P>
<P>
   Rogers (11-9), dropping breaking balls on the corners at will,
limited the Indians to two runs and eight hits. He walked four and
struck out three in winning for the first time in four starts.
</P>
<P>
   It was the left-hander's 400th career appearance for the
Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   Kapler's two-run double in the first tied him with Toronto's
Carlos Delgado for the longest hitting streak in the AL season.
Frank Catalanotto went 4-for-4 with a sacrifice fly and scored four
times as Texas bounced back after being shut out on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Ricky Ledee, traded from Cleveland to Texas last month, added
two RBIs.
</P>
<P>
   It was a bad day for the Indians on several fronts.
</P>
<P>
   Before the game, they learned that Manny Ramirez re-injured his
left hamstring and could be headed back to the disabled list;
right-hander Jaret Wright is facing season-ending shoulder surgery;
and the Indians missed a chance to gain ground on the AL
Central-leading White Sox, who lost the first game of a
doubleheader.
</P>
<P>
   Jason Bere (2-1) had been impressive in winning his first two
starts since being acquired by the Indians in a July 28 trade with
Milwaukee. The Rangers, however, never let the right-hander get
comfortable.
</P>
<P>
   The first three Rangers to face Bere all singled and scored in
the first to give Texas a 3-0 lead. Rusty Greer's infield single
off Bere's glove loaded the bases with none out, and one out later,
Kapler doubled in two runs and extended his hitting streak.
</P>
<P>
   Ledee made it 3-0 with an RBI groundout.
</P>
<P>
   Cleveland got a run back in the second on Sandy Alomar's RBI
single, but Bere was in trouble again in the third.
</P>
<P>
   Catalanotto doubled leading off and went to third on a
groundout. The Indians were going to intentionally walk Rafael
Palmeiro, but Bere's outside pitch sailed over catcher Sandy
Alomar's head, allowing Catalanotto to score.
</P>
<P>
   Kapler hit his second double and Ledee singled him home to put
the Rangers ahead 5-1.
</P>
<P>
   Texas added two more runs in the fourth on Luis Alicea's RBI
triple and Catalanotto's sac fly.
</P>
<P>
   The Indians blew a chance to get back in it in the fourth when
they put runners at second and third with none out. But Jim Thome
got doubled off second on Wil Cordero's lineout and Sandy Alomar
popped to third.
</P>
<P>
   Greer hit a two-run homer, his fifth, in the seventh to make it
9-1.
</P>
<P>
Notes: Tuesday's game was the 500th in Jacobs Field since the
ballpark opened in 1994. Cleveland is now (306-193 coming in) at
home. Of the 496 home games -- there have been three regular
doubleheaders -- 467 have been sellouts. ... Texas LHP Darren Oliver
will start for Triple-A Oklahoma on Saturday night as he begins a
rehab assignment. Oliver is on the disabled list with weakness in
his pitching shoulder. ... Cleveland's pitchers gave up just 16
runs during the six-game winning streak. ... Rogers has the
Rangers' lone complete game this season.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-08-00 2207 </TRAILER>
