<HEADLINE> Annan Shocked at Attack on U.N.  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- Secretary-General Kofi Annan appealed to
Afghan authorities on Tuesday to track down the gunmen who ambushed
and killed seven relief workers last week.
</P>
<P>
   The seven Afghans, who worked for the U.N.-supported mine
clearing program, were among 12 people shot and killed Saturday in
western Herat province. The Taliban religious militia that controls
90 percent of Afghanistan and the opposition accused one another of
carrying out the attack.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement read by deputy spokesman Manoel de Almeida e
Silva, Annan said he was ''shocked at the depth of the violence of
this unwarranted attack on humanitarian personnel that included the
torching of the two vehicles being used by the victims.''
</P>
<P>
   He sent condolences to the victims' families and called on all
sides in the Afghan conflict to apprehend the gunmen and bring them
to justice.
</P>
<P>
   ''The secretary-general hopes that urgent steps will be taken to
ensure the safety of humanitarian personnel and civilians in
Afghanistan,'' the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   The U.N. mine clearing program announced it would suspend the
activities of the 5,000-strong program Thursday and observe a day
of mourning to commemorate the dead.
</P>
<P>
   Devastated by years of continued civil war, Afghanistan is one
of the most heavily mined countries in the world. Several foreign
funded agencies are working to clear the land.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
