<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-08 22:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Manhattan judge issues restraining order against union vandalism  </HEADLINE>
By SAMUEL MAULL
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) - A Manhattan judge issued a temporary restraining
order against strikers at Verizon Communications late Tuesday after
hearing that supervisory workers at the telecommunications company
had been obstructed, threatened and assaulted.
</P>
<P>
   State Supreme Court Justice Louis York said he found that the
strikers, members of the Communications Workers of America, pelted
people with eggs, surrounded cars and jumped up and down on them,
yelled profanities at workers, blocked entrances and exits and
committed other unlawful acts.
</P>
<P>
   The CWA's lawyer, James Reif, told York that he should not
penalize the union for a ''handful of incidents'' by ''a handful of
individuals.'' He said Verizon knows who the people are and should
have had them arrested.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Masder, political director of the CWA, said the union had
passed out a booklet detailing the dos and don'ts of lawful
picketing.
</P>
<P>
   Al Luzzi, of Passaic, N.J., vice president of CWA Local 1101,
said that if he learned of anyone acting unlawfully on a picket
line, he would remove him from the picket line and give him another
job.
</P>
<P>
   But York said he believed ''the illegal acts were performed and
nurtured not only by union members but by people in authority at
the union.''
</P>
<P>
   York ordered pickets to stay at least 10 feet from Verizon's
facilities, work sites and buildings, and to permit enough space
for at least two people to walk side-by-side to and from those
facilities.
</P>
<P>
   York granted the restraining order at Verizon's request after a
nearly five-hour hearing Tuesday afternoon. Witnesses testified
that service had been knocked out in several areas because wires
and cables were cut at control stations.
</P>
<P>
   ''These kinds of acts cause harm to the public,'' the judge
said. ''We cannot deny that the public has been harmed.''
</P>
<P>
   Verizon's lawyer, Christopher Parlo, told York that Verizon had
recorded 381 acts of vandalism in New York State since the strike
started Sunday. Negotiations continued Tuesday and officials
reported making some inroads.
</P>
<P>
   The restraining order issued by York is similar to those Verizon
obtained earlier this week in courts in Pennsylvania and Delaware.
</P>
<P>
   The company has said it would offer a $25,000 reward for
information that leads to successful prosecution of assaults on
company employees or damage to company property.
</P>
<P>
   A total of 87,200 workers are covered by the contract that
expired Sunday. Robert Masder, CWA political director, said 32,000
of those workers are in 27 locals in New York State.
</P>
<P>
   In granting the restraining order, York implied that the court's
intervention might be needed because, ''I do think it has been
shown that the police cannot offer adequate protection.''
</P>
<P>
   York told lawyers for both sides to return to his courtroom
Monday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-08-08-00 2213 </TRAILER>
