<DOCNO> APW20000808.0196 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-08 22:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vandalism reports surge as strike enters third day  </HEADLINE>
By KALPANA SRINIVASAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) - Telecommunications giant Verizon
Communications said Tuesday it has been subjected to hundreds of
acts of vandalism to its facilities and threats to managers trying
to cross picket lines since workers went on strike over the
weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Union leaders, who are bargaining here to replace contracts that
expired Sunday for 87,200 workers, said it was unfair to suggest
their members are responsible.
</P>
<P>
   The company said it would offer a $25,000 reward for information
that leads to successful prosecution of assaults on company
employees or damage to company property. The strike affects 12
states - from Maine to Virginia - and the District of Columbia.
</P>
<P>
   ''Verizon will insist on being able to operate the telephone
network, and it will insist on being able to do that in safety,''
said Eric Rabe, spokesman for Verizon, which formed from this
summer's merger of Bell Atlantic and GTE.
</P>
<P>
   The talks adjourned late Tuesday night with no evidence of
progress.
</P>
<P>
   The company did not attribute unions as the cause of the
vandalism, but said indications of union responsibility were more
clear in situations where managers tried to enter facilities and
had rocks, bottles and eggs thrown at them.
</P>
<P>
   It said police were investigating some of the 455 incidences of
threats to workers, vandalism and assaults. About 230 of those took
place in New York, Rabe said.
</P>
<P>
   ''We don't have any problem with peaceful picketing,'' he said.
But the company will ''not tolerate'' threats to the safety of
employees, he said.
</P>
<P>
   In New York, a judge issued a temporary restraining order
against strikers late Tuesday after hearing that the company's
supervisory workers had been threatened and assaulted. The judge
ordered picketers to stay at least 10 feet from Verizon's worksites
and buildings. The restraining order only affects picketers in New
York state, although similar orders have been issued this week in
Pennsylvania and Delaware.
</P>
<P>
   Union officials called unfair any suggestion that unions might
be involved, and noted that the company experiences acts of
vandalism on any given day. They also chided the company for
seeking restraining orders in various parts of the region to limit
picketing.
</P>
<P>
   ''Verizon would be better advised to concentrate its attention
and resources on reaching a settlement and ending a strike, rather
than seeking to block CWA members engaged in peaceful picketing,''
said the union's president Morton Bahr.
</P>
<P>
   The strike affects the District and 12 states: Delaware, Maine,
Maryland, Massachusetts, New Hampshire, New Jersey, New York,
Pennsylvania, Rhode Island, Vermont, Virginia and West Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   At the bargaining table, CWA and the International Brotherhood
of Electrical Workers continued to tussle over issues including the
shifting of work to other areas, a union concern stemming from the
merger that created Verizon. Particularly, union members fear that
the company will reroute service calls - and therefore jobs - from
the old Bell Atlantic territory into cheaper areas in GTE's region.
</P>
<P>
   ''As work becomes increasingly digitized, it can be moved
anywhere,'' said Jeffrey Keefe, associate professor of labor
studies at Rutgers University. ''It's certainly something that
would upset the membership if they see their jobs going away.
</P>
<P>
   Unions also are seeking greater ease in organizing Verizon's
wireless workers. On Tuesday, CWA alleged that the company has been
passing out anti-union materials to wireless workers in Woburn,
Mass.
</P>
<P>
   Verizon's Rabe said he couldn't speak specifically to that
claim, but noted that the company has certain rights under federal
law to distribute documents
</P>
<P>
   '''Anti-union material' is in the eye of the beholder,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The parties did make some inroads, agreeing to return to the
core company some internal wiring work that had been farmed out to
a lower-paying subsidiary.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides said there were no immediate plans to call in federal
mediators.
</P>
<P>
   Separately, Verizon reported Tuesday that second-quarter
operating profits totaled $1.97 billion or 72 cents a share at Bell
Atlantic and GTE, which completed their merger in June. Those
results were about 5 percent better than year-ago levels, but
Verizon also reduced its profit forecast for the second half of the
year.
</P>
<P>
   Verizon also announced agreement Tuesday to merge its high-speed
Internet business with NorthPoint Communications Group, an upstart
provider of that service.
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: Verizon Communications: http://www.verizon.com/
</P>
<P>
   Communications Workers of America: http://www.cwa-union.org
</P>
<P>
   International Brotherhood of Electrical Workers:
http://www.ibew.org
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
