<TEXT>
<P>
 Tuesday, Aug. 8, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Source: Firestone To Recall Tires
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   DETROIT (AP) -- Bridgestone/Firestone Inc. will recall about 20 million of
its tires tomorrow for light trucks and sport utility vehicles that have been
implicated in accidents resulting in more than 40 fatalities, a source familiar
with the decision said today. Most of the Firestone ATX, ATX II and Wilderness
tires are on Ford Explorers, the top-selling SUV, but the recall will include
tires on all brands of vehicles, the source said. The source also said the
recalled tires will be replaced by other Firestone tires.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Annan Shocked at Attack on U.N.
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- Secretary-General Kofi Annan appealed to Afghan
authorities on today to track down the gunmen who ambushed and killed seven
relief workers last week. The seven Afghans, who worked for the U.N.-supported
mine clearing program, were among 12 people shot and killed Saturday in western
Herat province. The Taliban religious militia that controls 90 percent of
Afghanistan and the opposition accused one another of carrying out the attack.
In a statement read by deputy spokesman Manoel de Almeida e Silva, Annan said he
was ''shocked at the depth of the violence of this unwarranted attack on
humanitarian personnel that included the torching of the two vehicles being used
by the victims.''
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Aristide Party Wins in Haiti
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   PORT-AU-PRINCE, Haiti (AP) -- The electoral council announced the results
Tuesday from the final run-offs in Haiti's drawn-out elections, confirming that
the party of former President Jean-Bertrand Aristide won dominant control of the
legislature. The results came from run-off elections held July 30 for 10
lower-house seats in districts where balloting had been delayed. Aristide's
Lavalas Family party won five of the seats, according to the election council.
Opposition candidates took four while the determination of the final seat was
postponed because of irregularities.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Buchanans Claim Reform Victory
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   LONG BEACH, Calif. (AP) -- The Reform Party split loudly today as supporters
of founder Ross Perot walked out of a closed meeting, leaving backers of Pat
Buchanan inside and the party's future in question, just two days prior to its
nominating convention. ''We have won,'' claimed Buchanan's sister and campaign
manager, Bay. ''It's Pat Buchanan's nomination.'' But foes were seeking to block
the conservative commentator from the party's $12.5 million in federal campaign
funds if he wins the nomination.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Gore-Lieberman Begin Campaign
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) -- Democratic presidential campaigner Al Gore today
introduced running mate Joseph Lieberman at a rally. Sen. Lieberman of
Connecticut credited Gore with barrier-busting ''chutzpah'' and said they would
work to ''renew the moral center of this nation.'' With a Jew on a major party's
national ticket for the first time, Gore said, ''We will tear down an old wall
of division.''
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Chile Court Ends Pinochet Immunity
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) -- Pinochet made a surprise appearance at dusk at the
front door of his home to acknowledge cheer and applause by scores of
supporters. Chile's Supreme Court lifted Gen. Augusto Pinochet's immunity from
prosecution on Tuesday, paving the way for the former dictator to be tried on
human rights charges. But chances for a quick trial appeared slim. Pinochet's
supporters in Congress announced a bill to try to block a trial of the
84-year-old Pinochet on grounds of health. Pinochet had not been seen in public
since attending the funeral of a former aide on July 16.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
FDA OKs Corticosteroid Inhalant
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- An inhalant drug that can be used by asthmatic children as
young as 1 year was approved today by the Food and Drug Administration. The
drug, sold under the brand name Pulmicort Respules, is a corticosteroid
formulated for use in a nebulizer, a type of fogging machine. The drug will be
the first corticosteroid approved for the very young. Dr. John Jenkins of the
Food and Drug Administration said the drug can be used by asthmatics between the
ages of 1 and 8.
</P>
