<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Navy Detains 11 Puerto Rican Youths  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN JUAN, Puerto Rico (AP) -- The U.S. Navy detained 11 more
protesters Tuesday, all young people who broke into its training
ground to try to stop military exercises on the outlying island of
Vieques, a spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   The protesters cut through a fence and were caught by military
police at about 5:30 a.m., spokesman Jeff Gordon said. He said the
detainees were members of a youth group but was unsure of their
ages.
</P>
<P>
   A statement from the United Vieques Youth said its members would
try again.
</P>
<P>
   ''We cannot continue letting the U.S. Navy trample our people
and rob us of the right to a healthy and dignified life,'' it said.
</P>
<P>
   Protesters claim 60 years of bombing and other exercises on the
island has stunted its economy and damaged the environment and
islanders' health, charges the Navy denies.
</P>
<P>
   The Navy detained 32 women who broke onto the training range
Monday. They were charged with trespassing and freed until trial by
a federal magistrate.
</P>
<P>
   The protesters did not disrupt exercises by the USS Harry Truman
battle group, which began maneuvers on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ''These attempts to disrupt the exercises have utterly failed,''
Gordon said.
</P>
<P>
   The Navy owns two-thirds of Vieques and has used it for training
since the 1940s. After an accident killed a civilian guard on the
bombing range, which is on the eastern tip of the island,
protesters occupied the area and thwarted further exercises until
federal agents forcibly removed them on May 4.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, hundreds of protesters have been arrested trying to
re-enter the range.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
