<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-08 23:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cuban Doctors Happy To Be in Miami  </HEADLINE>
By ADRIAN SAINZ
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI (AP) -- Two Cuban doctors said Tuesday that they were
subjected to grueling conditions when they were jailed for more
than a month in Zimbabwe after declaring their intention to defect.
</P>
<P>
   Far from the squalor of southern Africa, in a banquet hall
called ''The Refuge,'' Leonel Cordova Rodriguez and Noris Pena
Martinez told a gathering of jubilant Cuban-Americans and local
politicians that they were grateful to be in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ''The jail was very rough,'' Cordova Rodriguez said. ''There
were 10, 12 people sharing one cell, and they tried to make our
lives as miserable as they could. We were afraid for our lives''
</P>
<P>
   After leaving Zimbabwe, they spent two weeks in Sweden on
temporary visas until departing Stockholm Monday for a 20-hour
journey to Miami.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're tired,'' said Cordova Rodriguez. ''But happy.''
</P>
<P>
   The doctors said their families may be subject to suffering at
the hands of the Cuban government for their defection, Pena
Martinez said.
</P>
<P>
   Pena Martinez's father, on another Cuban medical mission, has
been sequestered, she said. Cordova Rodriguez said his wife and two
children were ''taken from their home and told to move.''
</P>
<P>
   The pair detailed how a doctor's life in Cuba differs from that
of American doctors. Cordova Rodriguez said his monthly pay was
equivalent to $26 to go with a $50-a-month stipend.
</P>
<P>
   Pena Martinez, a dentist, and Cordova Rodriguez, a physician,
are hoping to find work as assistants in their fields. Both plan to
go through the lengthy process of getting their Cuban degrees
revalidated in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ''The first thing we're going to do is try to get our families
back from Cuba, where they're not safe,'' said Cordova Rodriguez.
''The next thing is we want to develop our professions.''
</P>
<P>
   Cordova Rodriguez, 31, and Pena Martinez, 25, were in Zimbabwe
on a medical mission when they sought refuge at the Canadian and
U.S. embassies in Harare, which referred them to the U.N. High
Commission for Refugees. But the Cubans disappeared June 2.
</P>
<P>
   The doctors accused Zimbabwean security officers of kidnapping
them and helping Cuban diplomats force them on a flight to Havana.
Air France refused to let them board during a stopover in South
Africa after the doctors slipped a note to a crew member saying
they were kidnap victims.
</P>
<P>
   The doctors were returned to Zimbabwe and jailed, while the U.N.
refugee agency demanded their release under international law. The
pair arrived in Stockholm on July 8 after the U.N. commission
negotiated their release.
</P>
<P>
   Cuba said the doctors betrayed the medical mission to aid
Zimbabwe's health service but denied any involvement in the alleged
kidnapping.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-08-00 2323 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000808.0207 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-08 23:30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> BWI Plans $1.3B Expansion Program  </HEADLINE>
By TOM STUCKEY
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANNAPOLIS, Md. (AP) -- The state will embark on a $1.3 billion
expansion of Baltimore-Washington International Airport -- including
construction of a people mover and a huge new parking garage -- to
relieve congestion at one of the fastest growing airports in the
country.
</P>
<P>
   A new terminal will also be built and another expanded as part
of the five-year program.
</P>
<P>
   The number of passengers using BWI has increased from 10.3
million in 1990 to an estimated 19.4 million this year, and is
expected to increase to 30 million by 2010, Gov. Parris Glendening
said.
</P>
<P>
   The governor and transportation officials scheduled a news
conference at the airport Wednesday to announce the expansion.
</P>
<P>
   Glendening said Tuesday that the plan will result in ''the most
dynamic BWI expansion plan since Harry Truman opened the facility
in 1950.''
</P>
<P>
   ''It's something that has to be done now,'' Glendening said.
</P>
<P>
   The $1.3 billion is in addition to $500 million already in the
budget for airport improvements.
</P>
<P>
   Glendening said the only serious complaints about BWI involve
lack of parking close to the terminal, congestion on the roadway in
front of the terminal and problems in getting from the garage to
the terminal.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the new money, $928 million, will be spent to solve
those problems, the governor said.
</P>
<P>
   The existing garage will be expanded to add 3,000 parking
spaces, and a rental car facility will be built to free 1,000
spaces in the garage now used by rental companies. A second garage
with 7,900 spaces will be built next to the expanded garage on what
is now the site of the Department of Transportation headquarters,
and a surface lot for 5,900 vehicles will be built near the two
garages.
</P>
<P>
   About $600 million will be spent to build an elevated people
mover, moving sidewalks, pedestrian bridges and to widen and extend
the terminal roadway.
</P>
<P>
   Dulles Airport, which outpaced even BWI's rapid growth rate last
year, recently announced a $3.4 billion expansion plan that
includes a fourth runway, a new concourse with 44 gates, thousands
of new parking spaces, and replacement of the unique mobile lounges
with a subway and moving sidewalks connecting the terminal to the
concourses.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-08-00 2330 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000808.0208 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-08 23:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lieberman Makes Prayerful Debut  </HEADLINE>
By CALVIN WOODWARD
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Even in this season of prayerful politics,
Sen. Joseph Lieberman's introductory remarks to the nation as Al
Gore's running mate stood out in evoking a deeply personal -- but
very publicly displayed -- religious faith .
</P>
<P>
   To those who have a sensitive tripwire on the question of how
much religion in politics is too much, Lieberman's speech did not
necessarily offend. But it stirred concern.
</P>
<P>
   ''If today's speech were the speech he gave every day, I would
be troubled about what he's trying to communicate,'' said Barry
Lynn of Americans United for Separation of Church and State.
''Americans are a religious people but they get very nervous,
properly so, when candidates appear to have more to say about their
faith than they do about their solutions to the country's
problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Normally in national politics it is the Republicans, influenced
for years by the religious right, who wear religion on their
sleeves.
</P>
<P>
   But Democratic Vice President Al Gore, a self-described ''child
of the kingdom,'' and Republican opponent George W. Bush, who
signed a proclamation in Texas making June 10 ''Jesus Day,'' are
both comfortable emphasizing their faith and their wish to involve
religious organizations more deeply in public policy while
respecting the line between church and state.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman, the first Jew chosen as a major-party vice
presidential or presidential candidate, asked the crowd in
Nashville, Tenn., to ''allow me to let the spirit move me as it
does to remember the words from Chronicles, which are to give
thanks to God.
</P>
<P>
   ''To give thanks to God and declare his name and make his acts
known to the people. To be glad of spirit. To sing to God and to
make music to God, and most of all, to give glory and gratitude to
God from whom all blessings truly do flow.
</P>
<P>
   ''Dear Lord, maker of all miracles, I thank you for bringing me
to this extraordinary moment in my life.''
</P>
<P>
   By the standards of American political discourse, Lieberman
crossed a line, said Kathleen Hall Jamieson, who studies campaign
rhetoric as dean of the Annenberg School for Communication in
Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   ''You would think you had just entered a religious service,''
she said. Political allusions to religion ''are not supposed to be
explicit or extended.
</P>
<P>
   ''If he is going to continue to open his speeches this way, it
is going to become problematic.''
</P>
<P>
   Political scientist Geoff Layman of Vanderbilt University, who
is researching religious differences between the two parties, said
he was struck that Lieberman would invoke religion ''in such a
powerful way'' given the attention being paid to his particular
faith.
</P>
<P>
   ''Of course, he did it in a nondenominational way,'' Layman said
from Nashville. Still, ''it might raise eyebrows among people who
are not very religious.''
</P>
<P>
   And according to his research, the Democratic Party is
increasingly drawing support from people who are not religious
while Republicans build their flocks from among the devout. Layman
attributes religion's sometimes prominent role in the Gore campaign
to the vice president's wish to separate himself from the moral
controversies that surrounded President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   But in a candid moment more than a year ago, Gore policy adviser
Elaine Kamarck told a newspaper, ''The Democratic Party is going to
take back God this time.''
</P>
<P>
   And the new Democratic platform suggests belief in God is a
universal attribute of the party, asserting ''Democrats believe
that God has given the people of our nation'' a mission for racial
and ethnic unity.
</P>
<P>
   Not that openly devout Democrats are new to presidential
politics. Jimmy Carter made no secret that he was a born-again
Christian, causing some nervousness among those who worry about
losing the line between church and state.
</P>
<P>
   ''I can't change the teachings of Christ,'' he said. ''I believe
in them, and a lot of people in this country do as well.''
</P>
<P>
   That was from a 1976 Playboy interview far more famous for his
confession that ''I've committed adultery in my heart many times.''
</P>
<P>
   Carter taught Sunday school while president, yet emphasized he
would in no way mix his Baptist beliefs with his presidential
responsibilities.
</P>
<P>
   Lynn noted that John Kennedy, in a campaign that made him the
first Roman Catholic president, declared his belief in the
''absolute'' separation of church and state, and played down his
religion.
</P>
<P>
   ''My concern is when politicians cross the line between
expressing their convictions and move to pandering for votes,''
Lynn said. ''I don't think that Senator Lieberman's speech today,
standing alone, demonstrates that pandering. But I would hope that
every political address he gives in the future does not begin with
a prayer.
</P>
<P>
   ''It would be wallowing in one's religious convictions.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
