<HEADLINE> Fox Promotes Free Trade Talks  </HEADLINE>
By KEVIN GRAY
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) -- Mexico's President-elect Vicente
Fox said Tuesday that his country and the members of South
America's largest trade bloc want to hold talks on a free trade
deal.
</P>
<P>
   Fox was in Argentina on the latest stop of a four-nation tour to
press his message that he seeks closer trade ties with Latin
America, after his country formed the world's largest trade bloc,
NAFTA, with the United States and Canada in the mid-1990s.
</P>
<P>
   Argentina, along with Brazil, Uruguay and Paraguay, forms
Mercosur, the world's third biggest free trade grouping. The
members have long talked of increasing ties with Mexico, Latin
America's second-largest economy.
</P>
<P>
   After talks with President Fernando De la Rua, Fox told
journalists that both leaders were of ''strong common agreement''
to begin talks on creating a free trade area between Mexico and
Mercosur.
</P>
<P>
   ''There is now a concrete invitation from the countries of
Mercosur to begin talks on negotiating a free trade agreement with
Mexico,'' said Fox, as De La Rua nodded his head beside him. ''Our
response is certainly positive. We want to make absolutely clear
that we are turning our eyes toward Latin America.''
</P>
<P>
   There was no indication of when such talks could begin, if an
agreement to hold them is finalized. More concrete steps toward
launching talks would have to wait until after Fox takes office
Dec. 1 for his six-year term.
</P>
<P>
   Fox was in Chile on Monday and continues on in his tour to
Brazil and Uruguay. Chile and Bolivia are associate members of
Mercosur.
</P>
<P>
   Fox said the time was ideal for Argentina, Chile, and Mexico to
seek to deepen their economic ties with each other, given that Fox,
De la Rua, and Chilean President Ricardo Lagos were all recently
elected.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're in a position to work together for many years, and this
is something we'd like to take advantage of,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Fox won a stunning victory July 2 that ousted Mexico's ruling
Institutional Revolutionary Party from the presidency after 71
years in power.
</P>
<P>
   He and De la Rua said they swapped ideas on how to better battle
ills afflicting their countries, including crime, unequal
distribution of wealth and obstacles to education and access to
technology.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-08-08-00 2336 </TRAILER>
