<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-08 23:49 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ABC Poll Looks at Lieberman  </HEADLINE>
By WILL LESTER
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Polling by ABC News immediately after the
selection of Sen. Joseph Lieberman as Al Gore's running mate found
that seven of 10 people think more favorably of the senator when
they hear he criticized President Clinton earlier than most
Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   A Monday night poll taken by CNN-USA Today-Gallup suggested the
presidential race is a dead heat, 45 percent for Bush and 43
percent for Gore, after polling all weekend gave Bush a
double-digit lead.
</P>
<P>
   CNN pollster Keating Holland said the one-night poll of 667
registered voters might reflect a shift in the race or might be a
blip caused by a quick poll. The poll had an error margin of plus
or minus 4 percentage points. Polls taken over multiple nights with
more efforts to call back respondents give a more reliable sample
of public opinion.
</P>
<P>
   Numerous polls have suggested that Bush had a lead after the GOP
convention of anywhere from 11 points to 18 points. The race has
been expected to tighten in coming days with publicity about Gore,
his running-mate choice and the Democratic National Convention.
</P>
<P>
   Holland said he'd seen signs in weekend polling of a closer race
between Saturday night and Sunday, but it would require more time
before it would be clear if Gore is closing Bush's lead.
</P>
<P>
   ''There is some concern that this was a one-night poll and
tremendous concerns that day by day in the mid-convention period,
every event has a big effect,'' Holland said.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Kohut of the Pew Research Center for the People and the
Press said one-night polls taken after an event like the Lieberman
announcement are more a measure of emotion than of settled public
opinion.
</P>
<P>
   ''Numbers like this are very ephemeral and reflect the emotion
of the moment, and therefore they last about a moment,'' Kohut
said. ''They give us a sense that public emotion was stirred.
Whether it will stay stirred in a Democratic direction remains to
be seen.''
</P>
<P>
   The ABC poll suggested public reaction to the Lieberman choice
was similar to response to the choice of Dick Cheney as the GOP
vice presidential nominee more than a week ago, with six in 10
saying they approve of each running mate. About the same number
said they don't know enough about either of them to have an
opinion. The ABC News poll of 513 adults had an error margin of 4.5
percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   And eight in 10 said Lieberman's Jewish faith would not block
them from voting for him, according to the ABC poll taken Monday
night. More than half said his faith was a positive attribute,
compared to 17 percent negative. Pollsters find mixed evidence on
whether people will honestly answer a question about personal
biases.
</P>
<P>
   A new poll in the battleground state of Michigan suggested that
Bush is ahead of Gore, but no more than the lead the Republican had
before the GOP convention.
</P>
<P>
   The Epic-MRA poll had Bush at 45 percent, 37 percent for Gore, 5
percent for Ralph Nader and 1 percent for Pat Buchanan in Michigan.
Bush led Gore 46 percent to 34 percent with 8 percent for Nader a
month ago. The poll of 603 Michigan voters had an error margin of 4
percentage points.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
